## Chapter 1: An Introduction to the Millionaire Mind

### The Millionaire Mind: Core Concept

- **Millionaire mind**: balanced approach to life — financially independent yet enjoy life, not "all work, no play"
- Most became millionaires in one generation from economic ground zero
- Not credit junkies or highly leveraged — live in fine homes with little/no debt
- Financial independence achieved without Spartan lifestyle (with constraints)

### The Oklahoma Millionaires (1983)

- Stanley interviewed 60 Oklahoma millionaires in first study of this segment
- All first-generation wealthy: business owners, executives, professionals
- Some were credit-dependent early but "went cold turkey" — broke the borrowing cycle
- **Gene** (late forties, salvage business owner): purchased foreclosed real estate from banks
- Gene's deal: 68 homes, shopping center, 5 apartment complexes from one institution

> **We [the lenders] own it all ... all of it. The business out there? ... You [borrowers] just run these businesses for us. You guys run them for us, the financial institutions.** — Credit officer to Gene

- Core lesson: **credit-dependent people are controlled by lenders, not truly independent**
- Contrast: those controlled by greed instead of credit — misers who shortchange family
- Neither extreme has the millionaire mind

> **I taught my sons and daughters that money is not their God. You control it ... not let it control you.** — Millionaire respondent

### The Research Foundation

- Book follows *The Millionaire Next Door*, expanding to wealthier population
- Only 4.9% of U.S. households have net worth ≥$1 million
- Can't just survey expensive homes — often occupied by **Income Statement Affluent** (big income, big home, big debt, little net worth)
- **Balance Sheet Affluent**: assets greatly exceed liabilities, little/no credit balances
- Hypothesis: certain neighborhoods attract Balance Sheet Affluent, repel Income Statement types

### Geodemographic Targeting (Jon Robbin)

- **Jon Robbin**: Harvard mathematician, expert in **geodemography** (studying people by defined geographic areas)
- Robbin built mathematical model estimating net worth for block groups/neighborhoods nationwide
- National database: 226,399 neighborhoods
- Selected 2,487 neighborhoods predicted to have high wealth concentrations
- Randomly sampled 5,063 households from target neighborhoods
- 1,001 completed responses; **733 were millionaires** ($1M+ net worth)

### Sample Characteristics

- Respondents lived in old, well-established, upper-middle-class neighborhoods
- Homes built in 1950s, 1940s, or earlier — not trendy new subdivisions
- Not "trendy" in home/neighborhood selection — millionaire mind avoids flashy estates
- Small outstanding mortgage balances or no mortgages

### Methodology Details

- Nine-page questionnaire with **277 questions**
- Data collected by **Survey Research Center, Institute for Behavioral Research, University of Georgia**
- Pretest: ad hoc sample of 638 millionaires (jumbo mortgage qualification criteria)
- Case studies from personal interviews and focus groups provide depth
- Earlier methodology described in *Journal of Advertising Research* (Stanley & Sewall, June-July 1986)

### Demographic Sketch of Millionaires

**Traditional Family:**
- Average: 54-year-old male, married 28 years (1 in 4 married 38+ years)
- Average 3 children
- 92% married; 95% of married have children
- 2% never married; 3% widowed

**Wealth, Income, Artifacts:**
- Average net worth: $9.2 million (median $4.3 million)
- Average household income: $749,000 (median $436,000)
- 20% have incomes ≥$1 million
- Typical millionaire never spent >$41,000 on automobile or >$4,500 on engagement ring
- Neither spouse ever spent >$38 for haircut (including tip)
- 1 in 4 never spent >$24 for haircut
- 7% of married didn't purchase engagement ring (passed down from relatives)

**Inherited Wealth:**
- Only 2% inherited all/part of homes and property
- 8% inherited 50%+ of net worth
- **61% never received any inheritance, financial gifts, or trust income**

**Geographic Distribution:**
- Found in 2,000+ well-established neighborhoods nationwide
- Examples: Shawnee Mission KS 66208, New Canaan CT 06840, Richmond VA 23224, Pittsburgh PA 15238, Fort Worth TX 76107, Kenilworth IL 60043, Columbus OH 43209, Atlanta GA 30327, Summit NJ 07901, Englewood CO 80110, Tulsa OK 74137

**Home Ownership:**
- 97% are homeowners
- Purchased current home average 12 years ago for $558,718 (median $435,000)
- Current average value: $1,381,729 (median ~$750,000)
- Benefited from home appreciation
- Generally small outstanding mortgage balances
- 61% live in homes valued >$1 million, but only 25% paid $1M+ for current home
- 10% purchased home in 3 years after 1987 stock market crash (searching for foreclosures)
- Home constructed 40 years ago (median) — 25% in homes built before 1936
- Only 10% in homes built in past 10 years
- 53% have not moved in past 10 years; 23% moved 2+ times in same period
- Only 27% ever had home built for them — prefer purchasing existing homes ("less time-consuming, costs less")
- **Attorneys are least likely to build homes**

**Vocations:**
- 32% business owners/entrepreneurs
- 16% senior corporate executives
- 10% attorneys
- 9% physicians
- Remaining third: retirees, middle managers, accountants, sales professionals, new-business officers, engineers, architects, teachers, professors, housewives
- Business owners richest overall
- Senior executives often multimillionaires (16% of millionaires, 26% of decamillionaires with $10M+)
- 50% of wives don't work outside home
- Working wives: 7% business owners/entrepreneurs, 5% sales, 4% middle managers, 4% attorneys, 3% teachers, 3% senior executives, 2% physicians
- 16% of employed wives currently retired
- Among decamillionaires: 2/3 have wives not working outside home; half of working wives work part-time

**Education:**
- 90% college graduates
- 52% hold advanced degrees

### A Brief Look Inside the Millionaire Mind

- Financially independent yet live comfortable, not extravagant lifestyle
- Cluster in upper-middle-class neighborhoods — fine homes, little/no debt
- Buy homes when others selling
- Married with children — family complements, not competes with wealth building
- **Self-made affluent**
- Vacation overseas ~once every 2 years
- Few have Phi Beta Kappa keys or SAT scores 1400+
- Love their vocations: **"It is not work; it is a labor of love"**
- Don't wake at 3-4 AM to accumulate wealth
- Many play golf/tennis regularly — strong correlation between golf and net worth
- Not into DIY tasks (those who are tend to have less wealth)
- Became rich without compromising integrity — **credit integrity as significant contributor to success**
- Not workaholics — socialize extensively with friends/family
- When work, work hard and focus energy to maximize ROI
- Plan investments, consult tax advisers, attend religious services, raise funds for noble causes
- **Positive correlation between lifestyle activities and net worth** — balance is possible
- Lifestyle activities bring contact with clients, customers, patients, suppliers, friends
- Best things in life are free or reasonably priced — son's sporting event, museum, bridge with friends "much less than a trip to a casino"

