## Chapter 1 (continued): Introduction

### Top Five Success Factors

**Millionaires' self-reported success factors contradict popular beliefs:**

- NOT looks, NOT supermodel figures, NOT lottery luck
- Parents, mentors, teachers, Wall Street gurus often "out of sync" with millionaire opinions
- Top five factors (in order):
  1. **Integrity** — being honest with all people
  2. **Discipline** — applying self control
  3. **Social skills** — getting along with people
  4. **A supportive spouse**
  5. **Hard work** — more than most people

- **Luck ranks #27 out of 30 success factors** (near bottom)
  - Millionaires define "luck" as uncontrollable factors (economy, market conditions)
  - No millionaire interviewed had positive words about gambling
  - Further discussion in Chapter 9

> "Many people, not just the millionaires in this country, have the five success elements mentioned above, but they are not millionaires today."

### Financial Risk vs. Gambling

- Strong correlation between **willingness to take financial risk** and wealth level
- Risk = investing in **yourself** (career, professional practice, private business)
- NOT about stock market gambling
- Most millionaires became wealthy in one generation by:
  - Seeing economic opportunities others ignored
  - Taking financial risk with promise of good return
  - Especially true for self-employed

**Leadership qualities:**
- Ability to sell ideas to employees and suppliers
- Ability to sell products to targeted audiences

**American economy rewards those who:**
- Provide products/services with strong demand
- Have few suppliers to fulfill demand
- Do NOT follow the crowd (in what they sell AND how they invest)

### Intellectually Gifted?

**Academic performance data (Table 1-1):**
- Average undergraduate GPA: **2.92** (on 4.0 scale)
- Average SAT score: **1190** (above norm, but not elite)
  - NOT high enough for selective/competitive colleges
  - Most millionaires did NOT attend top-rated schools
  - Graduating from top college rated as NOT important for success

**The 1190 SAT may be inflated:**
- Nearly 90% of A students recalled/reported SAT scores
- Only ~50% of C students could recall SAT scores
- SAT scores and GPAs are significantly correlated
- If adjusted for C students who couldn't recall: estimated **100-point reduction** from 1190

**Standardized test results showed millionaires were NOT:**
- Intellectually gifted
- Of law-school caliber
- Medical-school material
- Qualified to pursue MBA degree
- Smart enough to succeed (by conventional measures)

> "We often wonder how we as a group ever became so financially successful, given the fact that few of us were ever designated 'intellectually gifted.'"

**Question raised:** Are millionaires successful **in spite of** intellect, or **because** they felt they had to work harder to compensate for deficiencies?

### Assigned Reading: Robert J. Sternberg

**Reference:** *Successful Intelligence* (Simon & Schuster, 1996)

**Dr. Robert J. Sternberg's framework:**
- Successful intelligence has **three components:**
  1. Analytical intelligence (IQ, standardized tests)
  2. **Creative intelligence**
  3. **Practical intelligence** (common sense)

- Most millionaires economically successful because they're creative and have common sense
- Addresses questions throughout *The Millionaire Mind*

### School Days

**What millionaires learned beyond textbooks:**
- Tenacity
- Getting along with people
- Self-discipline
- Discernment

**Millionaire population includes many who:**
- Worked hard in school but did NOT graduate with all As
- Had SATs that were NOT spectacular
- Benefited from educational experience nonetheless

### The 900 Club

**Profile:** Millionaires who scored under 1000 on SAT

- 72% said school/college experience was:

> "Learning to fight for our goals because someone labeled us as having 'average or less ability.'"

- 93% indicated school/college was:

> "Influential in determining that hard work was more important than genetic high intellect in achieving."

- School enhanced abilities to:

> "Properly allocate time and make accurate judgments about people."

**Key insight:** Not just core courses — **Discipline 101** and **Tenacity 102** were critical parts of school experience

### Warren Bielke Profile

**Warren Bielke** — created **$1 million scholarship fund** at his old Minneapolis high school

**Scholarship criteria:**
- Ten students per year with average grades, good attendance, positive attitude
- Receive ~50% of college education cost at state school
- Must work to earn the rest
- Required to live on campus (close contact with people from different backgrounds)

**Bielke's philosophy:**
> "The smart kids, sometimes it's too easy for them. Sometimes they miss opportunities because they don't have to get involved and work so hard. The average kids get involved and come across more opportunities."

> "I think success really involves the situations you get yourself into and the people you meet. No one can be successful by themselves. It's the relationships that you develop with the people around you. Throughout my life, I've had people who helped me do better."

**Current role:** Vice president of investor relations, **Advanced Bio-Surfaces** (Minnetonka, MN)
- Company developing polymer for osteoarthritis treatment (clinical trials)
- Seventh medical-device company for Bielke in start-up/initial financing

**Background:**
- Raised by single mother who worked 12-hour days at dry-cleaning store
- Worked at gas station at night
- Mother's example: foundation for discipline and hard work
- High school counselor convinced him to take SAT — results "not great, but good enough" for four-year state school
- Lived in college dorm — students and professors showed "another path through life"
- Ended with C-plus average

> "I wasn't a great student. I ended up with a C-plus or ? average. But without this counselor guiding me to go to college, I would have taken a full-time job at the gas station."

**Advice to average students:**
> "It sounds like a cliché, but it's the effort you put in: It's how hard you work. Honesty is important, too. People will invest in you if they believe you are honest and hardworking. That's what happened to me."

> "Somewhere I read, 'It's not really how smart you are, it's how you are smart.' I can't tell you how many Ph.D.'s I've had working for me. They are very, very smart people, very good at their specialties. But they're working for me."

> "You've got to take advantage of the different opportunities that present themselves to you in life."

### Roberto Goizueta Example

**Not at the top... wrong** (profile heading)

**Roberto Goizueta** — former CEO of Coca-Cola

> "... He did not finish at the top of his class. But not for lack of trying... . Grades did not come easily. [And even one of his professors said] ... I would not have expected him [Roberto Goizueta] to become chief executive of the Coca-Cola Company." — David Greising, *I'd Like the World to Buy a Coke* (John Wiley & Sons, 1997), pp. 14-15

**Key question:** Could it be that Goizueta learned much more in college than he was given credit for on his grade transcript?

## Courage and Wealth

### Self-Made Millionaires Have Courage

**Core trait:** Courage to take financial risk given the right return

**Important distinction:**
- Having courage to take financial risk ≠ being a gambler
- Few millionaires gamble at all
- **Inverse correlation:** Higher net worth = less likely to gamble
- Yet **positive correlation** between taking financial risk and net worth

**Financial risk ≠ gambling**
- Most common form: **choice of occupation/vocation**
- Disproportionately high percentage of millionaires/multimillionaires/decamillionaires are:
  - Self-employed business owners/entrepreneurs
  - Self-employed professionals

**Why self-employment is risky:**
- No employer backing you up
- If you fail to deliver what market demands: out of business tomorrow
- May lose every dollar in assets

**Millionaire mind-set on self-employment:**
- NOT "scenario of failure" — risky **not** to be self-employed
- Being self-employed = **control of own destiny**
- Profits made are yours
- No ceiling on earnings

**Millionaires said:**
- Think of success, not failure
- Take risk but **study probable outcomes**
- Do everything possible to enhance odds of generating returns
- Eliminate/reduce fear and worry by:
  - Practicing believing in ourselves and hard work
- Bolster belief in ourselves by:
  - Focusing on key issues
  - Preparing and planning to succeed
  - Being well organized to deal with big issues
- Some conditioned minds through **mental toughness from competitive sports** ("athlete's heart")
  - Refers to physical AND mental tenacity and courage

**Role of religious faith:**
- 37% reduce fears/worries about critical financial decisions by calling upon **strong religious faith**
- Those with strong religious faith have higher propensity to take financial risk

### Vocation Vocation Vocation

**"Ace" definition:** One who excels at something (also fighter pilots with 5+ victories)

**WWII fighter-pilot aces:**
- 1,285 pilots earned title during WWII (*Wall Street Journal*, Jan 29, 1999, p. W11)
- Most did it the traditional way (dogfights)
- Many eventually shot down themselves

**Two pilots "did it quite differently":**

**Sergeant "Paule" Rossmann** — mentor who invented unique approach
**Major Erich Hartmann** — "Ace of Aces" (352 confirmed in-air victories, 80+ total)

**Source:** Raymond F. Toliver and Trevor J. Constable, *The Blond Knight of Germany* (Blue Ridge Summit, PA: Aero Books, 1970)

**Rossmann's approach:**
- Suffered arm injury early in career that never healed
- Unable to dogfight (typical dogfight = victory to those with superior physical strength)
- Developed **compensating technique:** substituting calculating method for macho dogfighting
- **"See and decide prior to firing" method:**
  - Carefully planned each attack
  - Spent more time analyzing targets of opportunity than firing bullets
  - Attacked only when in **best possible position to win**
  - Focused resources at **ideal target** — one giving maximum return on investment

**Hartmann's results:**
- Used Rossmann's approach
- Survived 1,425 combat missions
- Never even wounded

### Applying to Economic Success

**Millionaires' realization:**
- Developed understanding of strengths/limitations **before finishing school**
- Realized they had "injured arm" / limitation
- Developed own unique strategy for becoming economically productive

**Most millionaires:**
- NOT intellectually gifted in analytical sense
- Did NOT receive all As in school
- NOT in 1400+ SAT club
- Decided NOT to compete in macho dogfight environments where superior analytical intelligence is requirement

**Did not score high enough for:**
- Law school
- Medical school
- Graduate school
- Major corporation hiring

**Response:** Many chose to be **self-employed** — hired themselves when other employers would not

**Millionaires "other than intellectually gifted":**
- Gifted in other ways
- Abundance of **common sense**
- Have **creativity**

> "How else can we explain their ability to discover economic opportunities that most so-called geniuses were unable to see?"

**Author's conclusion after 20+ years studying millionaires:**
> "If you make one major decision correctly, you can become economically productive. If you are creative enough to select the ideal vocation, you can win, win big-time."

**Really brilliant millionaires:** Selected vocation they **love** — one with few competitors but high profits

### Vocation = Foundation

**Building analogy:**
- Poor foundation (sand/swampland) = constant dogfight with shifting elements
- Can spend millions on structure above ground, but won't matter
- Constant battle you cannot win

**Bedrock foundation (ideal vocation):**
- Home easily withstands wind and rain
- Insulated from dogfight with elements

**Characteristics of ideal vocation:**
- You **love** the products you produce
- Affection for customers and suppliers
- Know more about niche market than anyone else
- Customers don't care if you were C student in college
- To them, **you are the one who is enlightened**

### Warning About "Intellectually Gifted"

**Danger for superior students:**
- Those told they're gifted often feel **economically invincible**
- Assume superior intellect → superior income and wealth
- In for "rude wake-up call"

**Too many select vocations filled with competitors:**
- All also have high analytical intellect
- May be one of hundreds of thousands of MBAs graduated in past 20 years
- Hired by major corporations because A-grade work at fine business schools
- Went directly from schools into **the dogfight**
- Unknowingly entered sector with very few top dogs and CEOs

> "Just ask a sample of middle-aged MBAs how many dogfights they've been in in the past twenty years. How many were shot down or had their jobs eliminated?"

**What they forgot:**
> "Sure, they were all bright. But they forgot one thing: choice of vocation. Where you will fight is much more important in winning than what you do once the dogfight begins."

**Even best/brightest MBA students lose most dogfights**

### Think Differently from the Crowd

**Central theme of book:** It pays to be different

**Millionaires say:**
- Became wealthy in one generation due to **selection of right vocation**
- Laws of economics and psychology in their favor
- Otherwise would be "swimming against the tide"

**Belief about general population:**
- Minority can honestly say current vocation allows full use of abilities and aptitudes
- Millionaires are different — **millionaire mind**
- Were wise in selecting ideal vocation given abilities, aptitudes, and strong interest in financial independence

**How vocation was discovered:**
- Only **3%** discovered via employment agent or headhunter
- NOT at job fair
- Many are **intuitive as well as creative**

## Choice of Spouse

**Popular notion debunked:**
- Marry a millionaire
- Marry son/daughter of millionaire couple (inherit pot of gold)
- OR don't marry at all (avoid sharing resources)

**Data strongly indicates neither hypothesis is true:**
- Choice of spouse IS important for wealth variations
- Most millionaires did NOT select spouse because of wealth characteristics
- NOT initially attracted because parents "had money"
- Wealth factor NOT rated as important quality contributing to successful marriage

**Marriage statistics:**
- Strong correlation between years married and wealth accumulated
- 92% of millionaires are married
- Only 2% never married
- ~2% currently divorced or separated

> "Are there certain economies of scale associated with being married, as opposed to being single? The data clearly show that the answer is yes."

### Two-Career Couple Myth

**NOT the prototypical millionaire household:**
- Higher couple's net worth = more likely wife does NOT work outside home
- Contrast with high-income (non-millionaire) married couples: nearly 70% of wives work outside home
- High-income households: wives employed as teachers, sales professionals, middle-level corporate executives, attorneys
- Decamillionaire households: only **~1 in 3** wives works outside home

**Millionaires tell us:**
- Typical millionaire couple married for **28 years**
- 80% believe "having a supportive spouse" was very important or important for economic success

**Spouse qualities:**
- Much more than physical attractiveness
- Qualities are **complements to building wealth**
- Part of the millionaire mind

**Further discussion in Chapter 6, "Choice of Spouse"**

### Paulette Rakestraw Profile

**Paulette Rakestraw** — CEO and owner, **AMS Corporation**

**Background:**
- Twenty-one-year-old divorced mother of toddler
- Building direct-mail business from apartment
- NOT looking for spouse when met current husband, **Von**

**What attracted her:**
- His caring demeanor
- Way he treated her daughter
- Today: very family oriented, likes spending free time with three children

> "We just clicked. He's real laid-back, very go-with-the-flow—just a good companion."

**Working relationship:**
> "We were together twenty-four hours a day—we lived together, worked together—but we never fought."

**Starting AMS Corporation (1988):**
- Previous employer had repeated bad experiences with mailing services
- "This is ridiculous. We're paying a lot of money for this, and it's not rocket science."
- Started hiring friends and family for projects
- Other companies asked her to coordinate mailing projects
- "I was just determined there was a need for this, and I was going to pursue it."

**Complementary personalities:**
- She is risk taker, he is not
- She is inclined toward action, he encourages thinking and taking time
- "Sometimes he has to rein me in and I have to push him along."
- "It's a good partnership all around: We kind of suit each other and bring each other back to earth."

**Financial focus difference:**
- He thinks about money, is big saver
- She focuses on building the company
- "My whole drive has always been I like doing this and I want to provide quality service."
- "He always thought, 'Gosh, you can make a lot of money doing this,' while my focus through the growth of the company has been service."

**Early days:**
- Lived and worked in apartment with $325/month rent
- When she wanted $800/month Yellow Pages ad, he said she was crazy
- "I did it anyway. I told him months later when the ad came out, and he was glad because it really made our phones ring."

**Today:**
- Many Fortune 500 companies as clients
- 50,000-square-foot office complex

**Qualities that attracted Paulette to Von:**
- Sincere, down-to-earth, polite, affectionate, even tempered
- Open-minded, accepting, wise, encouraging, cheerful, compassionate
- Initial judgment proven correct after 10+ years of marriage

## The Economically Productive Household

**Contradiction in shopping behavior:**

**Millionaire household stats:**
- Average annual realized income: **$749,000**
- Average net worth: **$9.2 million**
- Top 1% of income/wealth distribution

**Yet millionaires:**
- 70% regularly have shoes resoled and repaired
- 48% regularly have furniture reupholstered or refinished (instead of buying new)
- 71% develop shopping list before grocery shopping
- Nearly 50% buy household supplies in bulk at warehouse stores (Sam's, Costco)

**Millionaire mind-set:**
- Sensitive to variations in time and money associated with shopping/purchasing decisions

**Rationale:**
- Resoling shoes much less costly than buying new (same for refinishing furniture)
- "Time is money" — takes much less time to resole/refinish than shop for new
- Shopping list before entering supermarket:
  - Saves money, avoids impulse buying
  - Greatly reduces in-store shopping time
  - Prefer spending time saved working or with family/friends (not randomly walking in supermarket)

> "If you want to run a productive household, start thinking like millionaires. Adopt their mind-set."

**Thirteen productive actions discussed in Chapter 7, "The Economically Productive Household"**

## The Home

**Millionaire home choices often criticized:**
- Why pay $500,000+ twelve years ago for 30-40-50 year old home?
- Why only four bedrooms when many have three children?

**Reality:**
- Homes have appreciated significantly over past dozen years
- Very well constructed — many brick/stone, slate roofs, hardwood floors
- NOT modern homes

**Why select older homes?**
- Quality of neighborhoods
- **Homogeneous neighborhoods** in socioeconomic characteristics:
  - 90% residents are college graduates
  - Most are very successful people
  - But as group, highly productive business owners/executives/attorneys/physicians are **conservative or traditional** in home selection

**Modern/newer homes:**
- Likely to be much larger (5-8 bedrooms)
- Don't forget 20-foot vaulted ceilings, four Jacuzzis, saunas

**Why millionaires pass on new homes:**
- Homes ≠ automobiles
- New does NOT necessarily = better, improved, superior
- Culture trained to be "new sensitive" — new always preferable to old
- **Those with millionaire mind are not like most people**

**Downside risk in brand-new $1 million subdivision:**
- Filled with $1 million homes
- Who says homes really worth asking price?
- Where's the history, price-trend data? (None exists)
- What types of people buy expensive homes in brand-new neighborhoods?
  - Tend to be **Income Statement Affluent** ("Big Income, Small Net Worth")
  - Enamored with "new" and gadgets
  - Currently lives in older neighborhoods where home value = $1.4 million

**People in older neighborhoods:**
- Different kinds of people
- Tend to be **Balance Sheet Affluent** (high net worth, little consumer credit)

**Reality:** People who accumulate wealth tend to live/buy homes in well-established neighborhoods
- Only minority of millionaires ever have homes built for them
- Many reasons discussed in Chapter 8, "The Home"

**According to millionaires:**
- Never pay initial asking price for any home
- Willing to walk away from any deal at any time
- Most have mortgages, but **40% have no mortgage at all**
- Less than 5% have outstanding mortgage balance of $1 million or more
- Only ~34% have mortgage balance outstanding of $300,000 or more
- **Median outstanding mortgage:** just under $100,000 (or ~7% of current market value)
- "We are not, as some people refer to them, **credit types**"

**Part of mind-set:**
- Purchase homes that appreciate in value
- Part of appreciation = function of high-quality public schools in area
- Sending three children to public schools (grades K-12) saved hundreds of thousands over private-school expenses

> "Most people, even those who do not earn anywhere near the incomes we generate, can still benefit from our orientation toward the home."

## Lifestyle

**Millionaire activities differ from stereotypes:**

**What they DON'T do:**
- Same things as jet-setters and beautiful people
- Overall activities "mostly from Dullsville"
- Only 3% took ocean cruise around world last year
- Only 4% skied in Alps
- 20% DID vacation in Paris last year (some trips partially subsidized by "business purposes")

**What they DO:**
- 85% consulted with tax expert
- 81% visited museum
- 68% engaged in community/civic activities
- Little/no "do-it-yourself" activities:
  - Only ~19% mowed lawn in past year
  - Not painting homes or doing plumbing repairs
  - Millionaire mind: work hard at main vocation, enjoy rest of free time doing what is enjoyable

**Thirty-day diary of activities equally telling:**
- Activities not costly
- "Whether you are rich or not, the best things in life are free or close to it"
- Entertaining friends, studying investments, watching children play sports — not expensive, yet things most love to do

**Lifestyles:**
- Congruent with strengthening relationships with friends and family
- Many activities not substitutes for wealth building but **complements to it**

**Further discussion in Chapter 9, "The Lifestyles of Millionaires: Real vs. Imagined"**

