## Chapter 5: Vocation Vocation Vocation

### Case Study: Henry — Strong Religious Faith

- **Henry** deals with feelings of inferiority about lacking formal education through strong religious faith
- High mechanical aptitude, invented many products he manufactures
- Most successful product came from a vision one night — claims God revealed the innovation to him
- Many millionaires share this pattern: personal relationship with God helped overcome poverty and academic disadvantages

> "Be strong and of a good courage; be not afraid, neither be thou dismayed: for the lord thy God is with thee whithersoever thou goest." — Joshua 1:9

### Case Study: Mel — Real Estate in the Sun Belt

- **Mel** became decamillionaire through commercial real estate after military service
- Drafted into army, stationed in rural South — while buddies complained, Mel studied economic opportunities
- Before discharge, found foreclosed property for $7,000 — even his father (astute businessman) advised against it
- Mel bought anyway, defying "Yankee" prejudice against the South
- Saw the town as intercept point between North and South, recognized early industrial growth
- Leased building for $100/month, eventually got $3,000/month
- Acquired more properties for $7,500-$10,000, now has three city blocks worth $175,000 total
- Built 50 stores in first 15 years, generating $750,000 annual income
- Used **OPM (Other People's Money)** for everything — never used his own capital
- Dad cosigned first loan after seeing Mel's research on growth potential and financial savvy
- Each new property financed through leases that covered loan payments before purchase
- Still working past typical retirement age, defines vocation as "landlord of a three-block monopoly"
- Religious faith: "the Lord gave us land... When it's gone there will be no more!"

### Discovery and Choice Factors

**Table 5-1 data:**
- 39% of millionaires discovered vocation through **intuition** (most frequently mentioned across all occupations)
- Business owners/entrepreneurs: 46% intuition, 39% studied profitability
- **Intuition** defined (Webster's): "immediate knowing or learning without conscious use of reasoning; quick and ready insight"
- 67% of millionaires are in four occupational groups that emphasize intuition

> "My financial success is a direct result of selecting a specific type or category of business."

**Most business owners are not millionaires** — owning a business is no guarantee, but careful selection greatly improves odds

### Case Study: Mr. Richard — Used Truck Parts Monopoly

- Upper-middle-class background, prep school, metro New York
- Now earns $700,000+ annually as **wealth accumulator** (Balance Sheet Affluent group)
- $12+ net worth for every dollar of annual income
- Wakes at 5:35 AM with a smile, can't wait to get to work

**Motivation:**
- Not financial worries — drive to meet business goals
- Wants to "get to the damn yard" and complete tasks daily
- Loves his career/business (key success factor: 46% rated "very important", 40% "important")

> "If you love, absolutely love what you are doing, chances are excellent that you will succeed."

**Table 5-2 data on choice factors:**
- Only 55% initially selected career for love of vocation, but 80%+ eventually cite it as explaining success
- 66% initially chose for "chance to be financially independent"
- 58% for "great profit/income potential"
- **81% selected vocation because it allows full use of abilities and aptitudes**
- 52% of business owners cited high self-esteem factor (vs 83% of physicians)

**Mr. Richard's path:**
- Faltered 8 years before finding his business — worked for others, underpaid
- Chose used truck parts for specific, well-defined niche
- Made himself the only real alternative for customers in that market
- Recognizes niche marketing expertise

**Dr. Jaw example:**
- Dentist who went to medical school to become MD, then combined both (DDS + MD)
- Specialized in jaw and teeth repair cases where jaw is damaged
- "Zeroed in on the most specialized field... making a killing because of his specialization"

### Nichers vs. Template Careers

- **Millionaire business owners are "nichers"** — little competition
- **Dr. Jaw** recognized opportunity: offer one-stop jaw and teeth repair (total package more productive than separate services)
- **Mr. Richard** — master of used truck parts in a profitable, growing region
- Both had prior experience in their chosen fields before specializing

**Mr. Richard's revelation moment:**
- Working at White Motor Company, boss asked him to sell wrecked truck to junk dealer for $500
- Two weeks later, junk dealer pulled engine and invoiced company for $500 plus another engine exchange
- Light bulb: entire truck worth 5-10x more when sold as parts
- Immediately recognized extraordinary business opportunity in "junk"

**Contrast with competitive fields:**
- 80% of Harvard associate professors denied tenure (among most intellectually gifted in country)
- Choice of vocation matters, but also level of competition within chosen environment
- Guidance counselors don't fully appreciate benefits of self-employment in ideal industry

### Example: The Struggling Attorney at Kinko's

- Met attorney at Kinko's — self-employed, competitive profession in author's hometown
- Needs part-time work to supplement income
- City Yellow Pages: 70+ pages of attorneys, but only 1 page for truck equipment/parts
- Mr. Richard sells parts exclusively for large tractor trailers — literal monopoly in geographic region
- Attorney is intelligent, passed bar, went to accredited law school — but one of thousands with 74 pages of competitors

### A Foundation of the Heart

- Selecting wrong vocation is like building home on poor foundation — will become heartache, may grow to dislike it
- **Mr. Richard is productive because work is joy to him**

**Why minority love their work:**
- Social status influences career selection
- Parents communicate (explicitly or implicitly) that suitable jobs involve wearing suits
- Parents push children toward professional careers (physician, attorney, CPA) or major corporations

> "My mother would say, 'Anyone can own a junkyard. Why did you go to college—not to own junk!'"

- Some middle-class people uncomfortable owning/operating blue-collar business
- **Mr. Richard** from upper-middle-class background but at ease with crew of "good old boys"
- "Intense need for social status" blinds people to significant economic opportunities

> "I surround myself with a lot of competent and capable people. It makes your life a lot easier. If you've got mediocre people, life can be miserable."

**Simple solutions overlooked:**
- Often the everyday problems define innovative businesses
- Hard-to-see opportunities not done before yield bigger rewards
- **Template career selection** = established training process (physicians, attorneys, CPAs follow set procedure)
- Mr. Richard and Dr. Jaw created unique, highly profitable businesses with little competition

### Vocation by Accident

**Jim R. — Executive Clubs and Country Clubs:**

- College dropout (University of Florida), joined army, earned commission
- Army provided key skills: discipline, organization, leadership
- After military, reentered college but had housing preference
- Rented house too big for his needs, sublet excess space to students, managed the property
- Tenants had no interest in typical landlord tasks (rent collection, furniture, utilities, lawn care)
- **Intuition moment:** discovered money could be made in real estate management
- Leased 24 homes and small apartments near campus, over 5,000 students as customers

### To Serve or Be Served?

**Jim's development company mistake:**
- Started real estate development thinking it was next step up status/economic ladder
- More creative, more prestigious than managing
- Developer supposedly in charge of contractors, subcontractors, suppliers
- **Reality:** lending institutions control developers
- Jim and others have "manufacturer's mentality" — believe lion's share goes to creators/manufacturers
- **Truth:** servers (property managers) often generate higher returns than developers/manufacturers

**The rock-and-roll dilemma:**
- Recording artist dreams vs. literary agent reality
- Author spends 3,000 hours writing book, agent spends 100 hours marketing it
- If book sells 1M copies at $20 retail ($3M total), publisher keeps $20M, author gets 15% royalties ($450K), agent gets 15% of royalties ($450K total)
- Author hourly wage: $850/hour for 3,000 hours
- Agent hourly wage: $4,500/hour for 100 hours (5x author's rate)
- "Smart people place their bets on the servers"

**Publishing reality:**
- 300,000+ books published yearly, 2/3 never reach bookstores
- Of 100,000 distributed, few sell 1M+ copies
- About 1/10 of 1% get close to 1M mark
- Thousands of authors spent thousands of hours, never sold more than 10,000 copies (under $10K earnings)
- Many brilliant in respective fields but don't know odds of profit

**Jim R.'s bankruptcy:**
- Age 28, largest personal bankruptcy in Florida history
- Had villa in Acapulco, Learjet, apartments in 12 cities, girlfriend in every city
- Highly leveraged lifestyle and business
- When interest rates climbed suddenly, young empire collapsed
- Went from penthouse back to parents' house (grandmother gave him keys to old Studebaker)

**Recovery:**
- Accepted position with large commercial real estate management company
- Learned "good lessons coupled with what I had learned during my business failure"
- Two years as regional executive, learned real estate finance
- Founded own management firm again, purchased investment properties
- Developed condominiums and apartments despite previous setback

**Market timing wisdom:**
- After several profitable years, sensed real estate market about to tumble
- Liquidated holdings just before crash, focused on property management business
- Major client: large commercial bank needing management for investment properties

**The country club opportunity:**
- Bank hired Jim as consultant for foreclosed real estate developments
- One property: large upscale residential subdivision with country club (18-hole golf, tennis, pools, clubhouse)
- Bank's dilemma: sell/liquidate builder lots and partially completed homes, or complete development?
- **Jim's advice:** only way to avoid losing millions was to complete development
- Bank not in construction business, wanted Jim to manage construction/completion
- Jim had construction management experience, accepted proposition

**Managing the club:**
- Construction was second nature to Jim
- Problem: prospective buyers wouldn't pay decent prices without country club fully operational
- Bank gave Jim sweetheart deal on purchase price and loan package to finance purchase
- Jim discovered owning/managing clubs far better than real estate development
- **Key insight:** no matter how good as developer, market dictates success or failure
- Property management provides steady income stream, allows full use of abilities/aptitudes
- Leadership and organizational skills match requirements for managing exclusive clubs
- Accidental vocation became career of choice for 20+ years

### Early Experiences

- Jim traces success back to his grandmother teaching him discipline, hard work, self-employment
- She tutored him in recognizing and capitalizing on economic opportunities
- Rapid ascent to millionaire status before age 28 (then bankruptcy, then recovery to current success)

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 5: Vocation Vocation Vocation (continued)

### Jim's Entrepreneurial Grandmother

- **Jim's mentor**: his grandmother, a "dyed-in-the-wool entrepreneur and farmer"
- Taught him to recognize economic opportunities from age six
- First business lesson: gave Jim half-interest in a cow + revenue from milk if he milked it daily
- Jim excelled — grandmother granted him ownership of the calves the cow produced
- She encouraged him to monetize cow manure: "I started bagging the cow manure from the barn. I sold it to people who used it to grow tomatoes."
- Parents provided basics, but anything beyond that Jim had to earn himself
- Grandmother's key lesson: ownership and caring for income-producing assets

> "Take care of this cow... this calf and they will give you milk." — Jim's grandmother

> "If you can't figure out how to make money for yourself, you're going to be working for the other fellow all your life." — Jim's grandmother

### Jim's High School Hustle

- Working for others = "cardinal sin" for Jim
- Freshman year: persuaded family veterinarian to hire him
- Worked afternoons, weekends, full-time summers throughout high school
- **Leveraged relationships**: raised golden retrievers as sideline, purchased dog food at wholesale through veterinarian employer
- Vet fees waived or heavily discounted because of relationship
- Sold puppies through employer's communications network
- College forced him to give up the "great job" and breeding business
- Didn't realize he already knew how to support himself from grandmother's lessons

### A Vocation Studied in College: Joe Smith

- **Joe Smith**: hardware business owner, small chain of extremely productive stores
- Only **36% of business owners** said college courses directly influenced vocation choice (Table 5-2)
- Joe's approach: if you knew your vocation goal in college, you'd have a road map
- Would take college seriously, select useful major, view every course through lens of "How can I use this given my chosen vocation?"

### Joe's Transformation as a "Collector"

- Joe became a **"collector of wisdom and ideas"** starting third year of college
- **Collector's mentality** crucial to economic productivity
- First two years: marginal student, no connection between school and hardware business
- **Turning point**: father died summer between sophomore and junior years
- Joe suddenly responsible for family business at age 20
- Attended state college part-time while running hardware business
- New mindset in every class: "What I'm going to learn... that's going to help me in this business"
- Transformed into straight-A student, graduated top 5% of class
- Accounting and business courses became critically important
- Even English mattered — had to write letters and reports
- Didn't just take over dad's operation — **transformed it into one of most profitable retail operations in country**

### Learning to Play Defense and Offense

- **Universal truth**: author has never interviewed successful business owner who isn't cost sensitive
- Defense (expense control) = foundation of productivity
- "A business that does not control costs is out of control"
- Joe learned "playing great defense" from accounting classes, applied daily
- Woke at 5:00 AM, arrived office before 6:00 AM to study cost data
- Analyzed sales and profitability for each item sold
- Positioned himself in front of flagship store before opening

> "During the day I would post myself up front. I would be sure that everybody was waited on... that they got what they needed... I figured that if anyone came to the business, they had a need. If I had to send them someplace else, we weren't supplying the people's needs. That is our philosophy." — Joe Smith

### Joe's Competitive Niche

- Major home-improvement warehouses opening in his region, but his business keeps improving
- **Specialization strategy**: developed market niche despite hardware competition
- Joe's philosophy: "Lots of little things... innumerable small amounts of things"
- Found niche by observing what customers needed that no one else carried
- Example: stainless steel pipe fittings — "You would not find them in any other hardware store... But there is demand so we'll stock a wide variety... It brings in trade."
- Also stocks O-ring cabinets
- "If you're open enough to observe, you will find a niche... and it will work"

### Joe's Customer Collection Strategy

- **Continually redefines vocation** with periodic updates based on customer demand
- Location strategy: stores at ideal intercept points, adjacent to concentrations of ideal hardware customers
- Not just physical proximity — must have **empathy for customer needs**
- Study their needs, stock stores to reflect those needs
- Many patrons = **millionaire homeowners** with pre-WWII homes needing parts
- Both DIY millionaires and those who hire repair talent shop at Joe's stores
- Personal service regardless of purchase size or uniqueness of problem
- Attentive clerks helping everyone

### A Generalization About a Specific (Author's Reflection)

- Students who get most from education = those who realize specific value of what they're studying
- Those with teaching/work experience before grad school had clearest understanding of course value
- Others struggled with motivation, asked "Why should Ph.D. candidate in marketing study mathematical statistics, macroeconomics, and microeconomics?"
- By program completion: equivalent of master's in statistics and economics (seven 4-hour qualifying exams)
- **Easier with clear future job description in mind**
- Author and classmates had taught before Ph.D. program — knew Ph.D. like "union card" for university hiring
- Kept vision of lecturing to attentive students while studying
- Vision: "readers who, hopefully, will increase their economic productivity by reading my material"

### Goal-Oriented Education

- **Must have a goal** to be economically successful
- Easier to complete "basic training" of college knowing what you'll do for rest of working life
- Pre-med students successfully complete rigorous courses because of clear goals
- Without goals, college = nightmare
- Determine what you want early → training becomes easier and more purposeful
- Many students with work experience eventually do well — ask the Joe Smiths
- Some successful entrepreneurs were C, D, F students working full-time while pursuing degrees
- Night-school route common, but all had **self-confidence from ongoing work experience and vocational goal focus**

### Vocational Discovery Through Stories

- Parents discussed economically successful people during mealtime
- Newspapers, magazines, books, personal experiences = sources for stories
- Doesn't take much time to share this information with children
- Benefits of teaching children to conceptualize "ideal" vocation early = enormous

### On Becoming a Collector (Author's Journey)

- Author became serious collector in **June 1980**
- Introduced to **Jon Robbin**, founder of premier geocoding firm
- Both served on task force for client
- Jon devised way to segment household population by neighborhood
- Concept = key to targeting marketing, advertising, promoting, distributing products/services
- Jon's statistical model estimated average net worth of each neighborhood in America
- Author's job: design questionnaires, survey methodology, analyze responses, prepare strategic report
- Jon ranked neighborhoods by average net worth
- Author surveyed millionaires in neighborhoods with highest concentrations of wealthy households

### The Revelation

- Jon's first presentation: "light went on inside my head"
- Many "upscale" neighborhoods had few millionaires
- Some had disproportionately large numbers
- **About half of all millionaires don't live in upscale neighborhoods**
- Author completely fascinated — Jon's presentation sparked much of his work since
- Became **serious collector of information about wealthy people**
- Kept collecting concepts, squirreling away facts about millionaires
- Uncertain how information would be presented or what dimensions would appear

### An Imaginary Dialogue: Finding Millionaires

- Author reads **trade journals** to find millionaires
- Not Wall Street Journal — publications targeting specific industries
- Examples of trade journals:
  - Pizza restaurant owner → *Pizza Today*
  - Muffler business → *Exhaust News*
  - Earth-moving equipment bargains → *Rock and Dirt*
  - Top veterinarian → *Bovine Veterinarian, Swine Practitioner, Equine Practice*
  - Even *Publishers Weekly*, *Tugboat Review*

### Why Trade Journals Matter

- Tom Stanley only person who interviews economically successful people featured in trades
- National media (ABC's 20/20, Wall Street Journal, Money, Success) ask Stanley to find millionaires
- **Nearly 10,000 trade journals** exist (Stanley's estimate)
- Most millionaires prefer being featured in industry "trade" vs. Wall Street Journal
- Enjoy status as *Turkey World's* cover story or *Exhaust News'* man of the year
- Stanley impressed: many trade journal owners became multimillionaires through their vocation

### The Pizza Today Founder

- **Gerry Durnell**: founding editor/publisher of *Pizza Today*
- Not originally from publishing, not journalism major in college
- Small Indiana pizzeria owner in Santa Claus, Indiana
- Wanted trade journal about pizza 15 years ago — none existed, so he started his own
- Knew market need existed because he was part of it
- Now major force in entire trade association, including *Pizza Today* and Pizza Expo

### Leveraging One's Collection (Author's Success)

- Eventually realized insights about wealthy would make exciting reading
- After years collecting data, interviews, research reports, surveys: hard to produce unique work
- When asked how long it took, refers to **June 1980**
- "May sound like lot of work for long time, but I love my job, and I'm never bored"

### Four Conditions for High Productivity

1. Love your work — excites you every day
2. Know chosen vocation allows full use of abilities and aptitudes
3. Get high self-esteem from work
4. Absolutely certain vocation will make you financially independent

- With these conditions: no difficulty focusing on goal and working at high productivity
- All revolves around **becoming collector of concentrated data and information**
- Too many people lack focus, are collectors of "anything" — not data, customers, marketable skills
- **Collectors** can read one newspaper and find several ideas for their vocation
- In 20 years, generate collection of treasure
- **Noncollectors** read thousands of newspapers, add nothing to collection
- May never start jobs or hate them
- Impossible to work at high productivity if you dislike work

### Finding the Ideal Vocation

- Key: find job well-suited to talents, easier to fall in love with it
- Should also have potential to make you rich
- Most millionaires had **several other jobs** before finding ideal one
- If stayed in first job (accepted right out of college) or job they disliked → would never be millionaires
- Often something in past (training, work experience) leads to ideal vocation idea
- Look for ways to fill market needs others ignored — **little or no competition**
- Start thinking and conceptualizing today
- Best vocations found in research = **genuinely unique**
- Even traditional areas can have uniqueness

### Tom Stanley's Discovery Factors: The Fieldston Story

- Author lived in small Bronx apartment in blue-collar section
- Quarter mile away: **Fieldston** — wealthiest neighborhood in NYC
- High concentration of extraordinary single-family homes
- Age 9, told sister: "I'm disgusted with marginal propensity of people in our blue-collar neighborhood to give to trick-or-treaters on Halloween"
- Suggested moving to Fieldston on Halloween night
- Sister and two friends cold-called home on Waldo Avenue in Fieldston
- **First home**: two acres in NYC, large gate, large wall, 150 feet from street, no lights
- Knocked 5 minutes, door opened: **James Mason**, distinguished British actor
- Nine-year-old Stanley: "Trick or treat"
- Mason: "Young man, I have no candy"
- Stanley: "Mr. Mason, sir, there are two parts to this equation. Where do you go from here?"
- **Mason's response**: "Young man, I'll give you all the silver in the house"
- Gave two handfuls of nickels, dimes, quarters, half-dollars
- Equivalent of what they would have received at 300 blue-collar households
- "That's what it means to be wealthy in America"

### The Milk Box Treasure

- After landing Mason, noticed lights on at English Tudor home across street
- Sign on front door: "Attention, trick-or-treaters. My husband is ill. Don't ring, don't knock. You'll find coins in the milk box."
- Stanley opened milk box: "Treasure Island!"
- Loaded with 20+ business envelopes labeled for group sizes (1-2, 3-4, 5, 6, 7)
- Eight-plus was big one, three envelopes for each category
- Took only one envelope for group of four, left Fieldston
- **Twenty years later began studying affluent in America**

### Finding the Right Fit: Dan R.

- How did Dan R. reach millionaire status before 40, earning $1M+ annually?
- Only 1 in 1,000 households achieves this in America
- Many factors, trials, errors involved
- Very wise when eventually selected ideal: **"Vocation vocation vocation"**
- Like vast majority of first-generation millionaires: selected perfect vocation
- **Perfect vocation** = one allowing full use of abilities and aptitudes

### Nine Jobs Before Success

- Dan R. took long time to introduce himself to focus group
- Author almost stopped him — thought recruiter made mistake
- Dan supposed to be high-performance sales professional millionaire
- Introduction = series of sales positions where he underperformed or was fired
- Author let him continue — good decision
- Dan documented **nine poor-performance jobs** before succeeding in tenth position

**Dan's Nine Failed Positions:**

1. After top business school marketing degree: sold calculators/electronic watches to retailers — "never seemed to get knack... didn't sell a lot. After two years asked to resign."
2. Major electronic games producer — "once again I couldn't get knack of selling, asked to leave about year and half later"
3. Start-up computer company — resigned after 9 months, "never selling one computer"
4. Small computer company — "didn't sell much of their product either," resigned after few months
5. Another computer company — didn't meet sales quota, asked to resign
6. Next job: "really doing well because I wasn't in sales... [I] was in marketing... But nine months later, company ran out of money and went out of business"
7. Start-up computer company, made $45K annually until last year made $200K — "But then market slowed up and company went out of business"
8. Another sales job — "company had problems with me because of low sales volume"
9. Company producing scanners at cash registers — "They let me go"

### Position 10: The Breakthrough

- Six years ago, found unique career closely fitting abilities and aptitudes
- Job entitled "sales professional" but much more than selling
- Required closing major deals + considerable market planning
- Understanding each customer's unique needs
- Preparing detailed proposals
- **Most important**: focusing on major accounts
- Gave Dan discretion in running business
- Dan viewed position as **market consultant** more than sales caller
- Almost immediately recognized he'd been ill-suited to previous jobs
- They were purely sales positions
- Dan consistently outperformed by other sales professionals because **he's a thinker, not sales commando**
- Most successful sales pros: aggressively call on largest number of prospective customers
- Preplanning relegated to making appointments
- Dan kidded by fellow sales pros as having "many plans, few clients"

### Dan's True Talent

- More than strategic planner
- **Extraordinary ability to uncover major market opportunities** and generate millions in revenue
- Took nine experiences with other employers before fully conceptualizing ideal position
- During nine equivalents of stations of cross, often agonized

> "I would sit in my car and drive all around... I would get so depressed because I had all this drive and was a really hard worker.... I was letting myself down and my parents down." — Dan R.

### The Searcher Finds His Calling

- Dan intuitively knew ideal vocation existed somewhere
- Kept looking for opportunity to fully utilize aptitude as highly intelligent, gifted marketer

> "If I could just find the right product and the right opportunities, I could do well." — Dan R.

- Computer industry gives major compensation to top-performing marketers
- Too broad — like finding room in large hotel with correct address but no room number
- Within "marketer of computer systems" domain, began search for ideal combination
- Never regrets previous nine employer experiences — helped conceptualize ideal vocation
- Six years ago convinced he'd discovered right opportunity allowing full use of abilities

### The $35 Million Deal

- December, after working (planning) five years, getting no orders from Home Depot
- Received **$35 million contract from Home Depot**
- Selling 6,000 handheld computers
- W-2 commission: **$1,033,000**
- Focus group clapped and cheered — all self-made millionaires with similar stories
- Great empathy for Dan's journey

### Stress and the Right Fit

- Contrary to expectations: Dan not constantly "stressed out" by intense productive efforts
- As most millionaires report: **stress = direct result of devoting effort to unsuitable task**
- More difficult/demanding mentally and physically to work in vocation unsuitable to aptitude
- Worse if knowing you're round peg in square holes
- Add realization vocation has little/no probability of making you wealthy → stressed out big-time
- Dan: more stressful earning $45K as marginally productive sales commando than closing multimillion-dollar deals
- Two scholars studied relationship between task environment and intelligence

> "Intelligent people are more likely to rely on intellectual effort in solving problems than those who have relatively low intelligence...." — Fred E. Fiedler and Thomas G. Link, "Leader Intelligence, Interpersonal Stress, and Task Performance," in Mind in Context: Interactionist Perspectives on Human Intelligence

- Dan's current employer appreciates his combination of aptitudes/abilities
- Most previous employers did not
- They preferred sales personnel who "knocked down doors" for immediate revenues
- Dan too creative, analytical, deliberate, intelligent for high productivity in "don't think, just sell" situation

> "The stressful situations require quick and preferably automatic responses; careful deliberation and weighing of alternatives will impede rather than assist with solution of the problem. Thus intelligence will correlate negatively with performance." — Fiedler and Link

### They See, But They Don't See

- **Don**: started successful business 25+ years ago, had three other highly successful businesses since
- Spent hour mulling over comments from other focus group members
- Deep in thought listening to discussion of "choice of vocation and economic opportunity"
- Author especially interested in Don's perspective on four-for-four hitting streak

> "You must be an opportunist... You must be an opportunist. Every one in this room is an opportunist! In your business, Dr. Stanley, how did you get into the book business? We all have different stories, but we all had an opportunity." — Don

> "Everybody out there has an opportunity to get into business... The opportunity to sell somebody something... Some can't see it. You have to be able to see it." — Don

### Combat Blindness Analogy

- Don's discussion about seeing opportunity = word-for-word from **Erich Hartmann** biography
- **The Blond Knight of Germany** (Raymond F. Toliver and Trevor J. Constable, 1970)
- **Major Hartmann**: often commented about "combat blindness"
- Wondered why so many pilots had difficulty seeing enemy target of opportunity
- Same problem as rookie pilot
- How possible that pilots with extraordinary eyesight (ophthalmologically measured) have combat blindness?
- Same pilots could read every letter on eye chart at greater distances than normal
- But couldn't see in real combat conditions

> "They see, but they don't see!" — Hartmann

- Same message Don related to group
- Some brightest people never see opportunity staring them in face
- Received all As in college, like fighter pilots with all As on eye tests
- But unless experienced, trained, really want to see opportunity → will always have combat/economic blindness
- Many think it's genetic trait explaining ability to see targets of opportunity
- Stanley believes people can be taught to see what others don't

### Hartmann's Training

- Based on scientific measures (eye charts, depth perceptions), Hartmann's eyesight didn't change much during 1,400+ combat missions
- Ability to see targets improved tremendously with mentors' help and experience
- Trained himself to focus receptors in sky areas where anticipated targets concentrated

> "He could spot aircraft... [at] a phenomenal distance, sometimes minutes before anyone else airborne with him." — Toliver and Constable

### The Vision of First-Generation Americans

- 1970s: fewer than 1,400 households in 1,000 had incomes of $100K+
- Certain groups had greater proportion
- Example: **Korean-Americans** about 3X more likely to have six-figure incomes than typical American (1970s Census data)
- Economic success of disproportionately large number of Korean-American households = direct result of **ability to see economic opportunities others overlooked**
- Amazing given backgrounds: most first-generation to US, not college educated
- English = foreign language
- Few inherited economic wealth — incomes from earned sources vs. trust accounts
- How possible that recent arrivals saw significant opportunities while most native-born Americans "see, but they don't see"?

### Stanley's Classroom Experiment

- For several years ran experiment in university classes
- Asked undergraduate, graduate, executive MBA students:

**"What are the top ten most profitable small businesses in America?"**

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

### Why Students Can't See Opportunity (Korean-Americans Example)

- Stanley's business students repeatedly fail to identify profitable business categories in America
- Not from lack of intelligence — business majors plan corporate careers, so profitability is "someone else's problem"
- Textbook writers/professors think profitability numbers "are not technically challenging to students"
- Real reason: ability to see economic opportunity is a function of **experience, training, and need**

**Korean-Americans vs. American-born students:**
- Korean-Americans came to U.S. with strong desire for financial independence — business ownership was "the only highway open to them"
- They correctly chose businesses with high probability of success and high profits
- Korean trade associations and cultural organizations provided information networks
- Informal interpersonal communication between successful owners and aspiring entrepreneurs

> "Among the most profitable categories of business in America during the 1970s was dry cleaning. Note that there are so many Korean-Americans in the dry-cleaning business today that one industry trade journal publisher had no choice but to publish two versions—one in English and the other in Korean!"

- Other profitable Korean-American categories: fruit/vegetable retailing and wholesaling, shoe repair, convenience markets
- Formula: provide good product or service at competitive price → economic success → financial independence

### Seeing Is Not Enough

**Don (self-made millionaire) on opportunity recognition:**

> "You have to be able to see it, then you have to believe you can do it."

- Belief in one's ability to succeed is a "very big foundation stone"
- Explains variation in performance among people in the American economy
- Belief in oneself = direct result of knowing the odds are stacked in one's favor
- Most businesses fail within 1-2 years because people don't know the real probabilities of success
- **Knowing the odds of success can make all the difference** — pick a long shot and college degree may not save you; pick a winner and the law of economics may not punish you

**Desire/emotional energy:**

> "You have to have something inside of you that wants to kill... You go out ... and take that opportunity, that chance... You [are] king of the mountain."

- The "something inside" that wants to kill is an **emotion or instinct that is vocation specific**
- Every product in Don's four businesses was a **labor of love**
- He loved conceptualizing products based on market needs, felt strong positive emotions about product development, design, marketing
- Without this emotional energy, none of his products would exist today

**Don's emotional energy made hard work fun:**
- Risks and lifestyle sacrifices rarely entered his mind — suppressed by focusing on the product/business that excited him
- Lesson: extraordinary economic productivity comes from finding the vocation that evokes and conjures up emotional energy
- But: enthusiasm alone can be overestimated when product love blinds the creator
- **Need objective third parties to evaluate ideas** — trusted advisers (CPAs, attorneys) separate emotion from economic reality
- One of Don's main advisers is his accountant

**Respondent on Don's success:**

> "You have the best description of your product... You did a wonderful job of explaining your company, your technology, and how your products work. You understand the technology, the fit in the market, and how it's going to benefit somebody else."

- Don's love is rooted in accurate estimate of the market's strong need for his product
- His motivation = envisioning buyers solving problems with his technology
- Great empathy for market needs, thrilled when technology fills those needs

### Market Democracy and Corporate Life

- Market environments in America are very democratic — reward people who fill a need regardless of physical attributes or background
- True in entrepreneurial environment and full-commission sales positions
- Market doesn't care about college grades, corporate etiquette, or Amy Vanderbilt's book on manners

> "I think the irony of it all is that you don't have to look like the [corporate] guys who have to look good."

**Don's corporate experience:**
- Grew up in blue-collar background, degree in applied physics
- Went to work for big company, dreamed of climbing corporate ladder

> "[Executives] in corporate structures just didn't live up to what I thought they would.... I put them on a pedestal. I got really discouraged being around them and the things they did. So... I started my own company... I was twenty-nine years old."

- Corporate vocation would never "light his emotional fire"
- Corporate experience helped him define where his talents/aptitudes would be best suited

### A Generic Author?

**Stanley's defense of his own vocation:**
- Audience member challenged: "Are you guilty of not practicing what you are preaching?" (competitive vocation)
- Stanley estimates several hundred thousand authors in America — direct competition would put him out of business
- **"I am not a generic author"** — specializes within the large population of authors/writers
- Writes about how common people become wealthy in one generation, topics others overlook
- "I am the 'Mr. Richard' of literature"
- Webster's defines **vocation** as "the special function of an individual or group"

**How Stanley planned The Millionaire Next Door:**
- Already written a bestseller, so hindsight is "twenty-twenty"
- But never doubted *The Millionaire Next Door* would be a hit
- Planned for many years, tested ideas in hundreds of seminars across America
- Two major concepts turned on attendees: (1) who the American millionaire was and was not, (2) *how* common people become millionaires in one generation
- Received requests for 200+ seminars/speeches in past seven years on these topics
- Had **information that no one else possessed** — survey-based insights into how to become financially independent

**Responses from audiences and millionaires refined his job description:**
- Provides answers to questions asked by many people
- When it comes to competitors, Stanley is like Mr. Richard's listing in the telephone book

**Mr. John Shmilgenko (real estate investor) on becoming wealthy:**

> "Playing Monopoly as a kid, I bought... properties because they were cheap... I took a similar approach in real life." (Tony Cook, "7 Secrets to Achieve Your Money Dreams," *Money*, June 1997, p. 76)

- Millionaire respondents encouraged Stanley to specialize, to monopolize
- Would never have succeeded as writer of love stories, mysteries, or generic fiction
- Stanley ancestry filled with writers/poets dating back to ancient Ireland — relatives think success is genetic factor
- Stanley's response: quality of writing doesn't explain demand for *The Millionaire Next Door*

**"The big issue is what is said, not how it is said":**
- Market Stanley selected defines what he does
- Knows from thousands of contact hours with public what they want
- Knows the questions they want answered
- Always felt confident about demand for his work

> "You don't need to be Shakespeare if you have excellent market research."

- Basic premise: giving the market what it wants and is not currently receiving from other authors

**Guilt about A students who never made bestseller list:**
- Most A student writers repeatedly ignore rule #1 in marketing: **me, me, me, is dull, dull, dull**
- A student writes beautifully with great elegance, grammatically sound, but criterion for selecting a theme is strictly me, me, me
- Writes about things of interest to him, forgets about the interests of the market
- Beautiful writing about Dullsville theme OR saturated competition = failure

**Stanley's advantage:**
- Great interest in main topic area AND strong market demand
- But first love was American history — realized competition in this area is extremely high
- If attempted to publish in American history arena: **"Me, me, me is dull, dull, dull"**

**Offsetting guilt:**
- Investment in time, energy, money — has a few million frequent-flier miles from visiting millionaires to tell success stories
- Hundreds of audiences asking for advice and suggestions
- Ideas in *The Millionaire Next Door* and *The Millionaire Mind* are product of personal hands-on market research, "the type that few writers ever have a chance to conduct"

**Advice to other writers:**
- Attended book fair with 20+ published authors, some taught creative writing, several were English professors
- Stanley felt way out of place

> "Tom, every one of these people can write, that is, state concepts, better than you. But not one of them ever had a book on the best-seller list."

- Authors who taught creative writing clustered in corner — spoke of style, creativity, burden of grading 130 papers
- One told Stanley he had little time to contemplate theme of next work, will have to come up with something soon — still "publish or perish"
- Best energy resources given to commuting, faculty meetings, teaching, grading papers
- What energy remains is allocated to next book
- **"I strongly believe that it's nearly impossible to write effectively if the book is relegated to a third or fourth priority"**

**Templates of productivity:**
- Much written about productivity of groups/businesses, but writing is an individual event
- Different from corporate sports
- Biographies of great team leaders and economically productive businesspeople do not apply to writing vocation

## Chapter 6: Choice of Spouse

> "Can you live forever? Marry the wrong spouse and every day will feel like an eternity. Marry the right spouse and life will be a joyful and perhaps even a rich experience."

### A Bumpy Road

**Million Dollar Round Table convention:**
- Five top-rated conventions held annually in America
- Invitation to be main platform presenter = genuine superstar status on lecture circuit
- Stanley invited to speak at Million Dollar Round Table (world's top-producing life insurance agents)
- Stanley was college professor from Georgia State, but head of speaker selection committee read about him in *Wall Street Journal*
- Stanley in front of 14,000 people, alongside distinguished speakers like **Eunice Shriver**, **Marvin Hamlisch**, **Lee Iacocca**

**Former football player story:**
- Outstanding professional career, played in four Super Bowls despite Vietnam War wound
- Delightful, down-to-earth man, successful transition from pro football to celebrity speaker
- Could write his own ticket, demand considerable fees, very selective in choice of clients
- Stanley suspected he was unusually talented and would surely become economic success

**Bankruptcy surprise:**
- Local newspaper headline: "Bankrupt Hocks Super Bowl Rings" (*Atlanta Journal-Constitution*, January 4, 1997, p. F3)

> "... [he] overcame Vietnam War wounds to play in four Super Bowls, filed for chapter 7 bankruptcy ... two days after selling his championship rings ... help pay back federal taxes."

- Former wife said in countersuit he "just wants to avoid paying her $837,948 from the sale of their home"
- Bankruptcy petition: already paid ex-wife $1.3 million in cash and property

**Divorce impact on net worth:**
- Divorce generally has devastating impact on individual's net worth (millionaires and nonmillionaires)
- 92% of millionaire households in America = married couple
- Millionaire couples have less than one-third the divorce rate of nonmillionaire couples
- Another factor distinguishing the millionaire mind: **ability to choose the right mate for life**
- Being divorced doesn't exclude one from becoming/remaining a millionaire — just makes it significantly more difficult

### The Economic Productivity of Marriage

**Research on marriage and wealth accumulation:**
- Studies consistently find significant correlation between length of marriage and wealth accumulation
- **Janet Wilmoth and Gregor Koso study** ("Does Marital History Matter? The Effect of Marital Status on Wealth Outcomes Among Pre-retirement Age Adults," Proceedings of the 1997 North Central Sociological Association):

> "Consistent participation in marriage results in significantly higher wealth."

- Conversely, people not married continuously over time have propensity to accumulate lower wealth levels

**Why marital status affects wealth:**
- Legal marriages have institutionalized features conducive to accumulating wealth
- Division of labor within marital relationship
- Economies of scale present in married-couple household not normally in single-person household
- Positive correlation between length of marriage and level of wealth holds true throughout all education and income groups

### Millionaires and Marriage

**Hypothetical divorce scenario:**
- If all millionaire couples broke up: one-third fewer millionaire households
- Assets divided, domestic overhead doubles, legal fees take share
- Millionaires stay married for reasons beyond economics

**Qualities millionaires seek in mates:**
- Unique ability to select mates with certain set of qualities
- Some qualities significant in explaining long-term happy marriages
- Other traits more directly related to wealth accumulation

**Characteristics of lasting marriages ("till death do us part"):**
- Unselfish, caring, forgiving, patient, understanding, disciplined, virtuous
- Helps if couple has similar interests, activities, opinions

> "What's Love Got to Do with It?" (Tina Turner reference)

- Love and deep affection underlie any happy marriage
- But affection can cloud judgment — if deeply in love with potential spouse who lacks traits like patience/understanding, may give grades too high because of emotional involvement
- Only later, through direct experience prior to divorce, can you recognize spouse's shortcomings

**Millionaires have early warning systems:**
- Uncanny ability to determine if prospective spouse is unselfish, caring, virtuous before becoming emotionally involved
- Accounts for high frequency of full-term marriages in this group

**What millionaires say about their spouses:**
- Down to earth
- My emotional backbone
- Unselfish
- Patient
- Has traditional values
- Understanding

**What initially attracted millionaires to spouses:**
- Physical attractiveness mentioned, but never the only factor
- Most had intuition about other qualities prospective spouse possessed

### Barbara "Bobbie" and Forester

- Married 30+ years, four grown children, own/operate three manufacturing companies
- Economically successful
- Bobbie raised in small western Kansas town near Colorado border
- Forester grew up on farm in southern Georgia
- Met at college mixer in Boston
- Both from modest backgrounds, both extremely bright, excelled in high school
- Families sacrificed to put together college fund, both received academic scholarships
- Forester attended MIT; Bobbie went to Wellesley

**Forester's first impression:**

> "The first thing I noticed was that her clothes were handmade. They were well made, but homemade."

- Fascinated with Bobbie — cute and charming, but wardrobe impressed him most
- Mother had made her clothes, told him a lot about background
- Obvious she came from modest means family, but sent daughter to top women's college
- Reasoned both Bobbie and parents had priorities ranked in proper order
- Bobbie impressed with Forester's presence at MIT given his modest background as farm boy

**Compatibility and business partnership:**
- Sensitivity about choice of ideal spouse — tested true for 35+ years
- Suited for each other, ideally suited to own/operate family business
- Early in marriage made trade-offs between buying expensive consumer goods and funding a business
- Business was their first priority
- No wonder they are financially successful today

**Lessons from frugal parents:**
- No one became wealthy by spending household's money on expensive consumer artifacts (clothes, new cars)
- No one became millionaire using consumer goods as status symbols while neglecting investments in private business or publicly traded stocks
- Both learned these realities from their frugal parents

### Marriage Vows and the Secret of Washing Cars: Common Interests

- Couples who share common interests tend to remain married
- Correlation between length of marriage and net worth
- But sharing of common interests and duration of marriage ≠ perfect predications of wealth accumulation
- If couple has common interest in spending all income, may shop together and stay married long time but unlikely to become financially independent

**Shared interests related to accumulating wealth:**
- Preparing household budget
- Planning and making investments
- Setting financial goals
- Owning and operating a business
- Couples who share these interests much more likely to attain millionaire status
- Makes more sense to purchase expensive new car out of gains from wise investments than from earned income

**Couple who bought $23,000 boat:**
- Purchase funded from part of dividends paid on just one investment in public corporation
- Both enjoy boating, also enjoy working together on family budget, studying investment opportunities, planning long-term financial goals
- Boating especially enjoyable because it's not a substitute to building wealth — boat was a reward
- Rewarded each other for exceeding goal of accumulating wealth
- Purchased boat with minor portion of gains from stock purchased nearly ten years ago
- Besides money invested, couple allocated hours of time to studying *Value Line*'s assessment of stocks, discovered this particular one
- Found it on shelf in local library

**Common interest in wealth-building activities:**
- Key for couples who wish to become financially independent
- Most common: owning and operating family business (like **B. and D. Ferguson**)

**The Fergusons:**
- Neither attended college, but household's net worth exceeds that of most college graduates
- Both ambitious and hardworking, keen interest in becoming financially independent to retire earlier than most couples
- Reasoned business ownership would provide highest probability of achieving goal
- Searched for category with high profit potential, found one they thought people would never recognize as generating high earnings
- Selected trade area with few competitors

**Mrs. Ferguson:**

> "Thank you for not including the car-wash industry as one of the businesses of self-made millionaires... The less public attention, the better... The reality is that there are many self-made millionaires in this industry."

**Starting capital:**
- Common belief: it takes millions to make millions
- Fergusons had different view — don't necessarily need to invest millions to become economically independent if start with small, efficient operation

> "At the age of twenty-six and twenty-nine, respectively, my husband and I leased a run-down, full-service car wash with $5,000 we borrowed from my husband's parents."

- $5,000 put couple in car-wash business
- Wise investment — thirteen years later, sold business for $750,000
- Fergusons found a diamond in the rough
- Most other married couples wouldn't have purchased "run-down" car wash
- Never bothered Fergusons that business wasn't glamorous and didn't denote high status
- Never concerned most customers viewed them as "strictly blue-collar"

**Couple's strength:**
- Beliefs were part of the couple's strength
- Any time one questioned career decision to "wash cars," countered with arguments:

> "Most car-wash owners (including my husband and me) are probably better off than our college-educated, professional customers. The sacrifices are definitely worth it long-term."

- Actually turned potential disadvantage of not attending college into advantage
- Motivated themselves into being frugal and productive by constantly reminding themselves they had accumulated more wealth than most well-educated, well-dressed, upscale customers
- Even during hard times (rained for several days, no customers), thought of long term, not minor setbacks

> "Long-term we will retire with more!"

### One in a Million: Attraction and Successful Choices

**Income and wealth not most important factors:**
- Not most important factors accounting for millionaire's successful marriage
- Not primary factor in initial interest discovered for man or woman ultimately married

**Why all this interest in what millionaires think makes up successful marriage?**
- Typical millionaire couple in America has been married 28 years
- 1 in 4 married for 38+ years
- Considering divorce rate in contemporary America, millionaires as group can teach us about finding right mate for life
- Choice of spouse is major factor in explaining variations in wealth
- Highly significant negative correlation between divorce and wealth
- Highly significant relationship between years of uninterrupted marriage and net worth

**Why are millionaires millionaires?**
- Made right decisions on several major issues in their life
- One of these is choice of spouse
- Not surprising spouse's physical attraction wasn't considered very important in millionaire's successful marriage

**Physical attractiveness:**
- Mentioned by nearly all respondents, does make some contribution
- Importance of this quality by itself is grossly overstated in current literature

**One respondent said:**

> "Given the choice, I prefer to be physically attracted to a woman who is intelligent, honest, unselfish, well-adjusted...."

- Most millionaires tell Stanley about "physically attractive" quality: almost never even consider marrying someone merely for "physically attractive" reasons

**Other important qualities:**
- Intelligence is important choice criterion in millionaire group
- Other very important qualities must also be present
- Future millionaires able to judge potential partners with respect to traits like **sincerity**, **cheerfulness**, **reliability**, **affection**

**How and where do millionaires acquire ability to distinguish ideal spouse from other candidates?**
- Recall discussion in chapter 3, "School Days"
- What was one of most important aspects of school and college that influenced millionaires in becoming economically productive adults?

> "Learning how to make accurate judgments about people."

- 88% indicated school and college experiences had significant degree of influence
- Dimension second in importance only to "developing a strong work ethic"
- School- and college-related experiences taught them to be sensitive to variations in qualities of people
- More interaction with variety of fellow students in many different social environments, better able to make accurate judgments about candidates for role of life partner
- Is this person truly sincere, reliable, and so forth? Critical part of spouse-selection process

**Parents' role:**
- Have you encouraged your children to be sensitive to variations in sincerity among boyfriends and girlfriends?
- Key issue: how sincere their friends are with all people — not just those they are trying to impress
- How do they treat people? Are they sincere because of nature and upbringing? Or able to turn sincere only when it benefits them?

**Intelligence as camouflage:**
- Not all intelligent people one meets in college have all other important qualities
- Quality of high intelligence can often act as camouflage
- Some people so taken with suitor's high level of intellect that suitor's deficiencies are concealed or overlooked
- Just as others are blinded by physical attractiveness
- If one places too much emphasis on quality like intelligence, may be insensitive to variations in sincerity, cheerfulness, reliability, and virtue

### Important Qualities

**Why most millionaire couples stay married:**
- Both husbands and wives have strong views about factors that contribute to successful marriage
- Know what components of lasting marriage are, have no difficulty describing them
- Successful marriage = direct function of presence of several qualities
- Both husbands and wives have almost identical views about these qualities in their spouses

**Table 6-1 data:**
- Nearly all males (99%) and large majority of females (94%) indicated being **honest** is important
- Both groups similar in frequency rating four other qualities as important:
  - 96% males, 92% females: **responsible**
  - 95% males and females: **loving**
  - 95% males, 96% females: **capable**
  - 94% males, 91% females: **supportive**

**Credit given to spouse:**
- Typical millionaire couple together for nearly 30 years, bond tends to be permanent as well as economically productive
- No matter if you ask husband or wife to explain household's productivity, answer is the same
- Each gives substantial credit to the other

> "For every 100 millionaires who say that having a supportive spouse was not important in explaining their economic success, there are 1,317 who indicate their spouse was important. Of the 100 who did not give credit to their spouse, 22 were never married and 23 were either divorced or separated. That leaves only 55 in 1,317 who believed that their spouse did not play an important role in their economic success."

**Mr. S., an entrepreneur:**
- Made it clear to focus group that family's business would never have been so productive without support of his wife of 38 years

> "I'll... hand it to my wife... If it hadn't been for her ... we couldn't do what we've done up to this point. We had five children. I never had to go to the doctor with her or with one of the children. She managed all of that... She did it all...."

**Common features among millionaires:**
- All state spouse is very supportive
- In order for mate to be supportive, must be honest, responsible, loving, and capable
- These are basic components of successful marriages among millionaires

### Don D.'s Supportive Spouse

**Mr. Don D. (self-made multimillionaire entrepreneur):**
- Provided excellent profile of supportive, responsible, capable spouse
- When Don was 29, asked wife about her views on his starting own business
- Explained certain sacrifices would have to be made
- First, would have to leave his well-paying corporate position
- Asked her opinion about financing start-up: "What if we have to sell everything?"

> "My wife said, 'What happens if you don't make money?' I said, 'Well, I'll get another job.' And she said, 'Fine.'"

**First business attempt:**
- Two years after Don started business, venture didn't make it
- Wife, who worked with him, never once complained
- Don returned to corporate life
- Five years later he quit corporate job — with wife's blessing and encouragement again
- Don started another business, success since founding in 1976
- Since then has started three other successful businesses

**Definition of "capable and responsible":**
- Wife not only took responsibility for almost all domestic tasks, also did much more
- Never had Don's technical expertise in physics
- But took initiative and learned about business and its technology
- Today, Don says with pride and admiration that two of the four businesses he started are owned and very efficiently managed by his wife

**Table 6-2: Top five qualities that initially interested millionaires in their spouses:**
- Intelligent: 96% all, 95% male, 99% female
- Sincere: 95% all, 95% male, 95% female
- Cheerful: 92% all, 93% male, 83% female (significant difference)
- Reliable: 92% all, 92% male, 91% female
- Affectionate: 91% all, 92% male, 88% female

> "I've been married thirty years ... my wife hasn't changed. Just the same person today. I could never imagine it without my wife... I'm sort of headstrong; she's a quiet, calming type of person."

**Perfect match:**
- Don indicated he and wife are perfect match
- Both recognize and admire each other's qualities
- Both possess many of five major qualities essential for productive and lasting relationship
- Mutually honest, responsible, loving, capable, and supportive

**Initial attraction factors:**
- Beyond physical attractiveness, five major qualities account for millionaires' first becoming interested in spouses
- Don like most millionaires: drawn to mate because she was **intelligent**, **sincere**, **cheerful**, **reliable**, **affectionate**
- How accurate were these perceptions developed during early stages of courtship?
- Nearly all millionaires say intelligence is important quality
- Asked group of ten millionaires to describe their wives, word *intelligent* was frequently mentioned

**What did men mean by "intelligent"?**

> "... My wife has the ability to learn and adjust to anything... Right now she could run the business better than I can."

**Educational background:**
- 90% of husbands and 85% of wives in millionaire household graduated from college
- Wives in particular did well — about 80% ranked in top quarter of class
- There are other ways to measure intelligence, but no matter how you define it, millionaires feel spouses have a lot of it

**Sincerity:**
- 95% of both husbands and wives became interested in future spouses because they were sincere
- Seems most were good judges
<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## The Money Factor (continued)

### Gender Differences in Valuing Spouse Wealth/Income

- **Women 4x more likely than men** to value high-income-earning potential in spouse
  - 49% of wives vs. 12% of husbands said high income was important (Table 6-3)
  - "Wealthy" quality: 37% of wives vs. 12% of husbands rated as significant
- **Top qualities for both genders remain consistent**: honest, responsible, loving, capable, supportive
- Millionaires emphasized repeatedly:

> He/she is honest, responsible, loving, capable, and supportive.

- Most millionaire couples could be "just as successfully married with much less income and with a fraction of their wealth"
- Both more sensitive to character qualities than wealth/income variations

### Traditional Gender Roles in Millionaire Households

- Most millionaire wives hold traditional values: man should be main income generator
- Only 12% of millionaire husbands feel otherwise
- Survey results align with **John Gray's** research on gender differences
  - Men have biological need to provide for women (John Gray, "Mars and Venus: Do Men Buy Love? Are Women Needy?" *Currency*, April 1998)
  - Women search for men with high-income-producing capabilities
  - Men often turned off by women who generate high incomes themselves

### Initial Attraction Data (Table 6-4)

**High-income-earning potential:**
- 59% of wives vs. 13% of husbands valued this initially

**Ambitious quality:**
- 82% of wives vs. 48% of husbands

**Wealthy quality:**
- 23% of wives vs. 9% of husbands

**Men more attracted to:**
- Well-dressed: 80% vs. 60%
- Virtuous: 79% vs. 61%
- Cheerful: 93% vs. 83%
- Encouraging: 87% vs. 80%

**Women value more:**
- Self-disciplined: 82% vs. 71%
- Secure: 81% vs. 71%

- Women who marry future millionaires attracted to the five "attractive" qualities PLUS ambition and high-income-earning potential
- "Wealthy before marriage" was not important for nearly 4 in 5 women
- Men seek the same five qualities but don't want to compete with spouse on money/income/wealth
- Wives often allow husbands to take breadwinner role

## The Criteria for Choice

### Millionaires' Predictive Success

- **Two-step process for accurate predictions:**
  1. Identify the RIGHT criteria compatible with long-term marriage
  2. Accurately predict whether potential spouse rates high on these criteria
- Most millionaires made these predictions long before becoming millionaires

### Contrasting Millionaires with General Population

- **Dr. Belinda Tucker (UCLA)** studied 3,407 general population adults (ages 18-55)
- Presented findings at 1997 American Psychological Association conference

**General population men prioritize:**
1. Physical attractiveness (highest)
2. Income criterion (salary/earning potential)

**Millionaire men prioritize:**
- Honest, responsible, loving, capable, supportive
- Physical attractiveness is only one of many qualities, not most highly rated

**General population women prioritize:**
- "Salary and earning potential" dimension rated highest—more important than attractiveness, education, or occupation

**Millionaire women prioritize:**
- Honesty, intelligence, ambition more fundamental than income/earning potential

### Dr. Tucker's Key Finding on Divorce Rates

> Satisfaction with your partner's financial contributions is strongly related to how you feel about your relationship and whether you feel you will stay in the relationship.

- **General population:** Both men and women would contemplate divorcing a spouse who lost a job
- **Millionaire couples:** Opposite attitude—willing to forgo high income for years while building wealth
- Example quotes from millionaires:
  - "Just after I was fired from my job... I started our business... Spent every bit of our savings... My spouse's income kept us alive for the first few but long, long years!"
  - "No longer will I feel apologetic for being so frugal... We are not cheap... only true entrepreneurs. We resist the urges to fall into the traps of our high-consuming neighbors who make more yearly income than we do. But we will retire with more wealth."

### Physical Attractiveness and Divorce Rates

- General population men rank physical attractiveness above all other criteria
- "Whatever happened to the belief that beauty is only skin deep?"
- To millionaires, attractiveness is only one of many qualities

> Perhaps our high divorce rate is related to the importance many men place on attractiveness. A woman might be attractive at the time of her wedding, but if she doesn't stay that way he may have grounds, in his own mind, for a divorce.

- **Tucker's findings:** Higher rate of husband-inspired divorces when woman loses attractiveness AND income-producing job simultaneously
- Wife may be blessed by divorce from such a man—he has history of unstable marriages

## Case Study: Victor and Sally Ganz

### A Case of Stability and Compatibility

- **Victor Ganz** and wife **Sally** married for 50 years
- Low-key Manhattan couple who invested in art
- Had passion for collecting art, toured galleries every Saturday
- Would sacrifice consumer goods like winter coats to make purchases

**The Ganz Collection:**
- Sold at Christie's auction for **$206 million** (1997)
- **Picasso's *The Dream***: purchased by Mr. Ganz in 1941 for $7,000, sold for $48.2 million
- Marriage was economically productive, not based on attractiveness and income
- Shared common interest in art
- Both willing to forgo consumer goods to invest in high-quality art
- Spent Saturdays walking through art galleries (usually no admission fees)
- Called themselves a "cheap date"

## EOC Inoculation

### Decamillionaire Father's Strategy

- Self-made decamillionaire contacted author after reading article in *Medical Economics* (July 1992)
- Article quote resonated with him:

> Wealth is more often the result of hard work, perseverance, and most of all self-discipline.

- Father had three daughters dating steady boyfriends:
  - One in law school
  - One recently graduated from top undergraduate college
  - One in senior year of college
- Father believed boyfriends might be **"wealth oriented" (WO)**—interested in prospective spouse because family is wealthy
- Feared suitors believe "road to wealth begins and ends with OPM, other people's money"

### The Test

- Father gave each daughter reprints of author's articles discussing:
  - Importance of hard work, discipline, frugal lifestyle
  - Detrimental effects of **EOC (Economic Outpatient Care)**
- Message to suitors: **No EOC!**
- If suitor lost interest after learning this, he was just WO

### Data on Millionaire Men and "Wealthy" Quality

- Only 9 in 100 married male millionaires initially interested because parents were wealthy
- Even those nine indicated other qualities were important
- None became interested solely due to "wealthy" quality
- At least 8 out of 10 attracted because future spouse was: sincere, down-to-earth, intelligent, affectionate, reliable, accepting, wise, cheerful, secure

## Wealth-Oriented Women

### Women More Sensitive to "Wealthy" Quality

- 23 in 100 wives vs. 9 in 100 husbands stated "wealthy" quality was important initially
- About 2.5 times more women than men attracted to mates because of "wealthy"

**Key insight:** It's the perceived wealth of potential mate's **parents** that is key
- Data suggests women dating someone's son aren't just interested in parents' treasure chest
- Even women who indicated "wealthy" was an attraction felt many more qualities were significant:
  - 90%+ also attracted to sincere, intelligent, affectionate, reliable, accepting, wise, cheerful, secure spouse with high income-earning potential
  - 85% attracted because of "ambitious" quality

### The Core Rule

> Never consider relying on other people's money to make you rich.

- Large majority of millionaires told author that economic qualities of in-laws had little to do with spouse choice
- Better to predict qualities of spouse than behaviors of in-laws
- Better to marry based on person-specific traits rather than ancestor/parent-specific traits

## Case Study: Peggy (Wealth-Oriented Woman)

### Lesson Number One

> If you are inclined to marry the son or daughter of a wealthy family, first make certain that it is, in fact, wealthy. The appearances of wealth can be deceiving.

### Peggy's Background

- Working-class background, earned undergraduate degree from major university
- Charming, attractive
- Parents impressed with wealthy people
- Both Peggy and parents assumed high occupational status = high wealth
  - Physician, attorney, accountant, or corporate officer assumed to be wealthy

### First Marriage Mistake

- Selected spouse from prominent family, direct descendent of important people
- Father was well-known business leader
- Parents active in civic causes
- Large home, luxury vehicles, prestigious country club membership
- Sister was Junior League member
- **"All that glitters is not gold"**—Peggy couldn't distinguish gold from iron pyrite (fool's gold)
- Initially interested and married a young man because of "wealthy" quality
- None of the cited facts are perfect predictors of wealth variations

### Discovery After Marriage

- Spouse's family had been in financial difficulty for years, even before wedding
- Kept up the face of successful/prosperous family
- Peggy expected to receive a home, but **no EOC** in cash or equivalents was distributed
- Ultimate realization: husband told her she would have to go to work
- Marriage didn't last three years

### Second Marriage Success

- Determined to marry a wealthy man
- Past experience and intuition kicked in
- Accepted position at large trust company searching for a "convoy"
- Met and married affluent client of trust company, many years her senior
- **"Hit pay dirt"**—a multimillionaire
- Currently: he works, she does not; he spends, she builds wealth
- Open question: Will his financial balance sheet accommodate Peggy's hyperconsumption lifestyle?

### Lesson Number Two

> Even if your in-laws are very wealthy, you or your spouse may never receive a dollar's worth of inheritance or even EOC.

- 46% of people in such situations never receive intergenerational transfer of wealth
- About 1 in 3 women who married men from wealthy families received average of $400,000 from spouse's relatives
- Translates to about $13,333 per year of marriage
- Associate's remark: **"She'd be better off financially working thirty years at McDonald's!"**
- Most people who marry for OPM are surprised
- Many wealthy parents believe **EOC dampens ambition**

## Wealth-Oriented Men

### WO Men Statistics

- More productive in quest for OPM than women
- For every 100 WO men, about 255 WO women
- Only 1 in 3 WO men received zero EOC or inheritance
- Large majority of WO men received about **$700,000** in intergenerational transfers

### Lesson Number Three

> About one-half of the women who marry WO men become housewives. Daughters of wealthy parents who are housewives are among the most likely to receive EOC. Conversely, most WO women marry men who are economically productive. Wealthy parents give the fewest number of dollars of EOC to their most productive offspring.

- If WO person marries productive mate, the more the productive person earns, the less likely they'll receive EOC
- Clear choice: can marry wealth *or* income, not wealth *and* income

### Lesson Number Four

> Wealthy parents prefer providing EOC to their grandchildren than to WO sons-in-law and daughters-in-law.

- For large majority of millionaire couples (80%+), other people's wealth was never important factor in spouse choice
- Nor was it important in explaining long-term, successful marriage

## Love vs. Honesty: Case Study of Henry and Sally

### The Relationship

- **Henry** (self-made millionaire) dated **Sally** for seven years before breaking off
- Henry loved Sally, she loved him
- Seemed proper fit: much in common, same lifestyle, opinions in harmony, same food/beverage preferences, both enjoyed clothes shopping

### The Problem

- Several years in, Henry discovered Sally had deliberately hidden $35,000+ outstanding debt
- Even more significant: **$20,000+ in loan defaults**
  - Credit card balances, auto loans, store credit accounts
  - All loans in arrears
- One creditor contacted Henry (listed as credit reference)
- Sally changed addresses multiple times, violated loan agreement
- Never paid back student loans despite completing undergraduate and graduate education years ago

### Sally's Deception and Plan

- Multiple creditors trying to track her down
- Henry was shocked—Sally gave no indication of credit problems
- She had well-paying job, new automobile, lovely clothes
- Appeared financially well off

**Sally's confrontation and revelation:**
- Initially denied it was a problem
- Said she was about to make good on outstanding loans
- Eventually revealed the real story and dollar amounts
- **Sally's plan:** Henry was well off financially; she confided in him about his money/net worth
- Sally felt Henry's income and net worth were keys to solving her credit problem
- Thought once married, she could use **OPM to pay off her debts**
- The "other people" in this case were just Henry

### Henry's Response

- Felt Sally committed serious breach of faith
- Independent of her subterfuge, he didn't wish to marry anyone who owed more than $35,000
- Sign of bigger problem: Sally was totally and completely irresponsible concerning money
- She'd betrayed trust of a man who prides himself on being fiscally responsible

### The Outcome and Lesson

- Henry broke off relationship
- Now wiser for next time
- **Next marriage will be different:** will never marry a woman without first running a credit check
- Says he'd be willing to provide next prospective spouse with income statement and balance sheet
- If information reveals problems, revelations are better coming before marriage than after
- Some problems can be solved—willingness to share information can strengthen a relationship
- Doubtful Henry would ever subsidize credit obligations of a prospective spouse

### Broader Insight

- Nearly all millionaires surveyed (95%+) felt "honest" and "responsible" qualities were significant in successful marriages
- Sally was unwise—thought Henry's love was so strong he wouldn't mind paying off her loans
- More than just loan payoffs: **Henry would have no part of a woman with a hidden agenda**

## A Class as a Convoy: Author's Personal Story

### Mementos and Luck

- Author keeps courtship photograph, movie/football tickets from first dates
- Only one grade book from 20 years as professor kept in top desk drawer
- Important symbol of courtship and good luck charm
- Reminder: "I am a very lucky fellow"

### Finding Janet

- Very lucky to find **Janet**, wife for 25+ years
- Not looking for bride when they met
- Author was 24-year-old instructor at University of Tennessee
- Teaching **Marketing 3110**, fall term, Section 33243, 2:20–3:10 P.M., Monday, Wednesday, Friday

### The Class

- High percentage of nice-looking young women
- **Janet** seated in row six, seat number one
- Noticed qualities during first period: attractive, attentive, well-dressed
- Opportunity to learn more about her throughout term
- From afar, appeared to have many attributes of ideal spouse

### The Benefit of the Class

- Teaching job didn't pay much, nor have many fringe benefits
- **Teaching that semester provided a convoy:** contained ideal spouse and mother for children
- "Ultimate lifetime benefit"
- Many other qualities more important than income or wealth
- **Janet has all of them**

### Early Marriage Years

- First three years in small apartment—all they could afford during three-year Ph.D. program with annual stipend of $3,600
- Janet cheerfully accepted secretarial position at university for $4,500/year
- Good thing they didn't have much money—little time to spend it given Ph.D. program rigors

### Janet's Support

- Typed all author's papers and dissertation twice
- Never complained once
- When dissertation committee wanted redo of 100+ page proposal on Friday with rewrite due early Friday afternoon, Janet retyped the rewritten proposal that night and much of Saturday
- Never had to ask for help—**Janet thrives on helping others**
- Applies to family, school, and civic causes
- "Ultimate in unselfishness"

### Janet's Frugality

- **Scottish background**
- Never enters food store without complete list and coupon folder
- Before buying new furniture, gives thought to refinishing or reupholstering what's already in house
- Have house full of "reprocessed" furniture
- Same sofa for 20+ years—fabric changed but guts are original

**First date revelation:**
- Ordered grilled cheese sandwich and Coke for lunch
- Author wondered: How could someone so well-dressed be such a "cheap" date?
- Later learned father was **salvage merchant**—specialty was quality women's wear
- Traveled all over America to bid on inventory of stores damaged by fires or natural disasters
- Mother once said: **"Everything Janet wore to college was in a fire, so I hope you will buy your children clothing that wasn't."**

### Janet's Family Background

- Janet's family members very respectful of one another
- Also unselfish, supportive, and cooperative
- Author visited parents' home several times during holidays
- Place filled with aunts and uncles and cousins
- All trying to help: clean up tables, serve beverages, take dog out, clean dishes, etc.
- "Almost like watching a musical play on Broadway"
- "Better than the Boy Scout's creed"

**Janet's mother on genetics:**
- Mother and husband married for 50+ years
- Believes both "came from people who are unselfish and supportive"
- Another factor: both sets of Janet's grandparents were farmers
- Qualities like unselfishness and respect instilled in farm environment
- Everybody works on a farm, including children

**Janet's mother's background:**
- One of eleven children
- Mother died when she was just four years old
- All children taught value of sharing household chores
- Mostly on their own: cooked, cleaned, shopped, did every chore associated with rural living
- Adversity encouraged them to respect and support one another

### Janet's Humility

- Embarrassed when author praises her
- Dislikes being in spotlight under any circumstances
- Once *People* magazine sent photo team for "family shots"
- Lead photographer insisted Janet be in picture
- Janet even more insistent about not being in *People*
- Photographer was no match for her
- Despite typing and editing all author's books, Janet did not wish to be in media
- Certainly deserved to be included in all photographs with best-selling author husband
- More basic things like family and close friends give rewards that are more satisfying

### The Other Guy (Rick)

- Glad Janet didn't marry "that other guy"
- **Rick** sat right behind her in class
- Author objected to his talking while lecturing
- Rick kept talking to Janet even though she didn't return conversation
- To keep harmony in class and isolate Rick, author **moved him to back of the room**

### The Dating Strategy

- Improper to date someone in author's class
- Had to wait until Janet was no longer a student
- Proper to reduce competition in meantime—Rick was moved
- Another problem: what if Janet decided to take other course author scheduled to teach following semester?
- Another semester to wait
- Something had to be done

**The intervention:**
- On several occasions told class they should take next course in sequence with different faculty member
- Better if students take courses from variety of faculty

### The First Date

- Janet took advice
- First date materialized when author bumped into her on campus
- Said hello, asked her to have lunch
- She looked surprised, maybe puzzled, but said yes
- **Was it luck or design?**
- Engaged within seven months, married about ten months later
- **"The class certainly was a top-quality convoy for me."**

## Lisa, A.K.A. Lisa Library

### College as Convoy

- Ideal spouse qualities (ambition, intelligence, discipline, physical attractiveness) can be found on college/university campuses
- "Convoy of convoys for ideal spouses"
- Many millionaires met spouse at college by chance—someone introduced Joe and Gloria or Bill and Helen
- All in target-rich environment
- If looking for intelligent spouse, odds high you'll find many on campus
- Quality people found in quality convoys

### Lisa's Background

- One of professor's enjoyable tasks: working with students of great merit and potential
- **Lisa** had straight A's in competitive undergraduate program
- Very high scores on Graduate Record Exam and Graduate Management Aptitude Test
- Charming and attractive
- Wide variety of interests and extracurricular activities

### The Research Project

- Enrolled in author's undergraduate course during fall semester of senior year
- Second week: Lisa and three classmates stopped by office, expressed interest in learning more about marketing area to which author devoted considerable time
- **Lisa was spokesperson for the group**
- Proposed group conduct research and write paper based on survey
- Didn't qualify for credit, but wanted to enhance knowledge in new area
- Thought project would enhance records for graduate school admission

### The Meetings

- Agreed to meet for hour or two each Monday morning during term
- Author updated them on project, provided direction and outside reading materials
- All went as planned for nearly entire term
- On Monday of second to last week of semester, **Lisa was absent for the first time**

### The Revelation

- Few weeks before, Lisa dropped off requests for recommendations
- Author delighted to support applications for three of America's top MBA programs
- Innocently asked: **"Where's Lisa?"**

> Didn't you hear? Lisa's getting married. She's not going to graduate school.

- Surprised because Lisa never mentioned being engaged
- Queried group; learned most were as unaware as author
- Backup leader informed: Lisa wouldn't be completing independent study program
- Didn't need it to bolster graduate school applications
- **Now getting married, no longer interested in graduate school**

### Lisa's Decision

- Decided to marry doctor in last year of medical school
- Someone she'd just started dating and quickly become engaged to
- All expressed surprise she'd abandoned major goal of graduate school
- Informant revealed: graduate school was her **number two goal**, just in case she was unable to marry a doctor

**The secret to goal number one:**
- Every night studied in medical school library—tip from mother
- Mother told her: if she married a doctor, she'd never have to work or be concerned about money
- Also suggested medical school library was perfect place to meet that doctor

### Author's Reflection

- Shocked by revelations
- Lisa was young scholar who could easily become major economic success by herself
- Incredible she had withdrawn prematurely from American economy
- Why did Lisa's mother strongly encourage her to marry physician?
- Literally pushing brilliant young daughter into perfect convoy: medical school library

### The Economic Reality for Women

- Five men for every one woman who achieves six-figure earned income
- Fewer than 10% of those earning seven-figure incomes are women
- Women, even in top-paying professions, earn only about 55% of what male counterparts earn
- "Economic deck is stacked against them"

### Millionaire Demographics

- Popular press celebrated predicted growth in female affluent population for 20+ years
- Survey research does not indicate much change
- 90%+ of millionaire population in America composed of married-couple households
- About half of other 10% made up of widows and widowers
- **In 80%+ of married millionaire households, it is the husband** who is:
  - Main breadwinner
  - Financial decision maker
  - Head of domestic investing

### Assessment of Mother's Advice

- How good was advice Lisa received from her mother?
- Author suspects mother was "sadly, rather intuitive about the economic odds facing her daughter"
- Still maintains Lisa, with extraordinary aptitudes, could have overcome them

## The Other Benefit of Night School

### Author's Role

- Student indignantly asked: **"What makes you such an expert about marriage?"**
- Author clarified: not a marriage counselor or psychologist
- Job is simpler: study productive people who earn high incomes and accumulate substantial wealth
- Underlying productivity: several factors, one very important relates to **choice of spouse**
- Who you marry and how long you stay married can be major determinants
- Correct selection = tide will be with you on journey to becoming productive household
- Doesn't ensure wealth, but surveying thousands of millionaires shows about 9 in 10 believe it was major factor

### Bad Choices

**Where people go wrong:**
- Initially became interested in spouse who was very charming
- Able to hide elements of faulty character
- Drank a lot even during early courtship stages, but partner felt he would "grow out of this college craze"
- Drinking continued throughout marriage
- Later found out: insincere, selfish, undisciplined, unreliable, prone to lose temper
- What happened to early pronouncements about great ambitions and self-designated superior intelligence?
- Fell for his sales presentation

**Where did first encounter occur?**
- Friday during happy hour at singles bar
- Perhaps some people luckier and found ideal spouse at similar place
- Hardly the ideal convoy to hunt for spouse

### Singles Bar vs. Quality Convoys

**Singles bar convoy ranking:**
- Where do prospective spouses rank on criteria millionaires use?
- Important millionaire qualities: ambition, intelligence, reliability, self-discipline, unselfishness, honesty, work ethic, respectfulness
- **Note:** 2 out of 3 millionaires indicated moderate drinker or abstainer quality also important in successful marriage

### Better Convoys

- If ambition and intelligence are important qualities, enhance chances by hanging out at night where they do
- **Suggest night classes at local university** are better place to hunt for spouse
- Can kill two birds with one stone

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Chapter 6 (continued): Finding Your Ideal Mate

### Alternative Mate-Finding Strategies

- College courses as prospecting grounds
- Can pursue degree or advanced degree while searching
- Noncredit self-improvement courses (computer programming, conversational Spanish)
- Strategic class selection: choose courses with high concentration of opposite sex
- Education classes tend to have more women; engineering and accounting have more men

### Terry's Dilemma

- **Terry**: early thirties, owned small professional-service firm, married with one child
- Recently decided to divorce, dreading "going back to the dating game"
- Had done singles bar route in mid-twenties, found current spouse that way
- **"Frog problem"**: you have to kiss a lot of frogs before you meet a prince
- Believed fewer princes exist in singles bars
- Process could take years via singles bar route
- Out of market for nearly ten years, felt insecure about dating ability

### Church-Based Singles Groups

- Author's advice: join a church group
- Churches have well-organized adult singles groups
- People with religious orientation more prone to respect traditional values
- Church environments more stable with formal membership systems
- Members can inquire about fellow church members more easily than bar patrons
- Singles groups affiliated with churches attract people looking for long-term relationships
- Members seeking traditional values, not one-night stands

### Miss Ann Geocodes Churches

- **Miss Ann**: intellectual, senior editor at major publishing company
- Recently divorced, postdivorce blues, considering moving to another city
- Questioned her ability to attract opposite sex
- Complained her city "had no eligible men to date"
- Author suggested church-related solution

### The Geocoding Strategy

- Miss Ann needed church group with high concentration of educated intellectuals with traditional values
- **Geocoding theory**: birds of a feather flock together
- People in particular neighborhoods have similar socioeconomic characteristics
- They tend to patronize nearby churches
- Author identified areas/neighborhoods with high concentrations of well-educated people
- Ruled out churches without active singles groups (religious sections of newspapers helpful)
- Newspapers carried advertisements including prices for residential real estate for sale
- Easy to identify "high-rent" districts
- Denomination not important to Miss Ann—suitable singles convoy mattered more
- One church emerged as winner: "mother lode" of well-educated professionals
- Contained attorneys, physicians, accountants, architects, executives, entrepreneurs
- Church wasn't in Miss Ann's neighborhood—she drove past other interesting churches

> "Finding a spouse is a serious business, and it generally becomes more difficult after one leaves school and grows in age and gray hairs."

### Active Participation Strategy

- Most singles spend more time shopping for automobiles than affinity groups
- Finding spouse is numbers game
- Greater concentration increases probability of meeting possibilities
- Give prospective spouses opportunity to meet you
- Millions of great prospects remain unattached year after year
- Once inside religious affinity group: **volunteer**
- Singles groups need guest speakers, organizers
- Few want job of organizing programs
- Advantages of being head of speakers' recruitment committee
- **Miss Ann can select anyone she would like to speak**
- Could identify successful single men who might write books about their experiences
- In process of recruiting speakers, could uncover prospective spouse on her intellectual plane
- Local business periodicals publish lists and profiles of successful people in various fields
- Author volunteered to be speaker (though married) to get ball rolling
- Having best-selling author discuss millionaires would make points with other members

## Chapter 6 (continued): The Meat of the Proposal

### John's Background

- **John**: waited patiently for author after two-hour corporate seminar
- Vice president of major corporation, earning over $300,000 per year
- Self-made millionaire
- Parents never rich but gave him ambition, integrity, work ethic
- High degree of common sense from parents
- Early in career faced tempting proposal, turned it down
- Never regretted decision—"always and still is his own man"

### The Christmas Proposal

- Senior year at major state university
- Had steady girlfriend **Becky**, also a senior
- Becky: attractive, sincere, down-to-earth, intelligent
- Couple developed great affection, decided Christmas holidays good time to meet parents
- **Becky's father**: founder/owner/manager of highly successful meat-processing and packing company
- Becky's mother: housewife
- Parents very pleasant, made John feel at home and wanted
- After long Christmas day, Becky and mom retired
- John left with Becky's father in den

### Mr. Meat's Background

- American success story
- Came from economic ground zero (family background and education)
- Became multimillionaire with meat-processing business
- **"Mr. Meat"** thought he was luckiest man in world
- Assumed every young man in America would want opportunity to work for him
- Eventual equity position possible
- John could become "Mr. Meat Jr."

### The Two-Hour Pitch

- Leading question: "John, you and Becky are serious about getting together, aren't you?"
- John admitted being serious about Becky
- Mr. Meat spoke for nearly two hours
- Verbal profile of trials and tribulations
- Focus on "opportunity" versus long odds of making it from ground zero to Mr. Meat status
- Well-rehearsed sales presentation
- Same presentation given to two young men now married to other daughters

### The Formal Proposal

**Employment and Lifestyle Opportunity: Son-in-Law and Senior Executive Wanted**

Requirements:
1. Willing to work for father-in-law Mr. Meat
2. Eventually given title of vice president
3. Salary generous, significantly above what recent college graduates receive
4. Agreeable to living near Mr. Meat and family, adjacent to other married daughters
5. Given home of their choosing
6. Excited about vacationing each summer with Mr. Meat and entire family
7. Free unlimited use of Mr. Meat's luxury beach house
8. Two-week summer vacation
9. Applicant and family expected to spend all time with Mr. Meat and family
10. Wife and children spend entire summer cost-free at beach
11. Applicant joins family on weekends
12. Mr. Meat's other daughters and families follow suit
13. Willing to work closely with Mr. Meat and two other sons-in-law
14. Become member of executive committee headed by Mr. Meat
15. May be given equity in business, prospect of taking over when Mr. Meat retires

> "This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity as well as a lifestyle and lifetime obligation. Becky's hand will be given only to the applicant who accepts employment from Mr. Meat. Those unwilling need not apply."

### The Assumptive Close

- Mr. Meat made "assumptive close" (Salesmanship 101)
- "I know exactly what you are thinking. You are saying to yourself, 'John, you are the luckiest guy in the world.'"
- Why would he think otherwise? Mr. Meat was two for two
- John never given real opportunity to respond
- Mr. Meat thought he signed up another son-in-law
- John went to assigned room, went to sleep
- Left for parents' home next day
- Spoke with Becky few times by phone before next semester
- She seemed excited about "family plan" her father proposed

### John's Decision

- Waited until back at university to break news
- No engagement, no marriage with family plan
- **Becky true to Mr. Meat more than beau's wishes**
- Probably loved John but not interested in marrying someone outside lifestyle designed by parents
- **John's need for independence**: strong need to be independent
- Found it insulting anyone would propose to dictate his lifestyle
- Mr. Meat in love with meat business, but John had no affection for it
- Not impressed with operating style
- Had great confidence in own abilities
- Excellent student at demanding state university
- Sights set on recruitment by top public corporation
- Corporate world had high-quality executive training, great opportunities

### Problems with the Proposal

- Wondered about productivity of hiring executives based on who they married
- If Mr. Meat's two other sons-in-law were losers, who would pick up slack?
- Common sense: nepotism not best way to select and promote executives
- Particularly incensed by potential domestic problems
- John and Becky would be given home by Mr. Meat, but whose name on deed?
- How would domestic disputes be handled?

> "John, this is my house. It is the house that my daddy paid for... so if you don't like the way I'm doing things, you can leave."

- Leaving would mean moving out of home AND giving up career as executive at Mr. Meat's operation
- Under such conditions John never be head of own household
- Disputes handled outside home, inside court of Mr. Meat
- He'd never thought Becky would be willing to live under such conditions
- Clearly more affinity for parents and domineering lifestyle than for future husband's orientation

### The Independent Path

- Given John's ambition and need to be independent, clearly made proper decision
- Today successful corporate executive, reached millionaire status on own
- Realizes struggle, self-made journey to success makes us strong
- Subsidies from Mr. Meats can make one dependent
- What if Mr. Meat dies suddenly? No intention of giving business to sons-in-law?
- Worse: merely looking for dependent stooges to dominate?
- How many Mr. Meats dangled prospect of business ownership in front of unsuspecting candidates?
- How many candidates looking for love and marriage but not emasculation?

### The Wealth Factor Warning

- Survey data very clear: many who select spouse because of wealth factor eventually disappointed
- Sometimes parents of spouse leave little or no wealth
- Other times parents only act rich but "big hat, no cattle" types
- **Better to marry for love, respect, and ambition than for spouse's ancestors and financial artifacts**

## Chapter 7: The Economically Productive Household

### Millionaire Household Practices

Millionaires productive in accumulating wealth AND running productive households:
- Having furniture refinished instead of buying new
- Switching long-distance telephone companies
- Never buying from telephone solicitations
- Having shoes resoled or otherwise repaired
- Using discount coupons when shopping
- Buying household supplies in bulk

### The Coupon Math

- People ask why millionaire would clip coupons
- Not about saving fifty cents today—about lifetime savings and investment
- Typical affluent family spends over $200/week for food and household supplies
- More than $10,000 per year
- During adult lifetime in current dollars: between $400,000 and $600,000
- Cut just 5% of this amount ($20,000-$30,000) and invest in top-ranked equity fund
- Given rate of return during past few years, amount earned would be more than $500,000
- Millionaires compute lifetime costs and benefits of activities with saving potential
- **High correlate of accumulating wealth**, one element in overall frugal game plan

### The Impulse Buyer Problem

- More than two-thirds of grocery store shoppers are impulse buyers
- Show up at supermarket without list or with short one
- Wander around store without game plan, spend more time searching
- More time spent, more money spent
- Proven time and again
- Without list, people buy things they may not need until later in week or at all
- Most millionaires do their own food shopping (not maid or au pair)

### The Ideal Shopping System

- One millionaire couple interviewed had ideal system
- Made maps of interiors of two food stores they patronized
- Included names and location of each category of product
- Made copies of maps, served as weekly shopping lists and planning templates
- During week when ran out of grocery item, circled item on map
- Planned menu purchases this way
- Menu items often included because of coupons and related offers

### Time Allocation Analysis

- Sounds like lot of work, but it's not
- Look at it another way: without list, without shopping plan, ask yourself:
- How much pleasure spending extra 20-30 minutes or more in favorite food store each week?
- What happens when don't plan ahead of time?
- Thirty minutes/week over adult lifetime: between 62,400-78,000 minutes
- 1,040-1,300 hours
- 65-81 waking days

> "It isn't very productive spending more than 62,000 minutes of your life in a food store—wouldn't you be better off allocating some of that time to planning investments, watching your son or daughter play baseball or softball, taking a few extra vacations, thanking the Lord for his wonderful blessings, upgrading your computer skills, exercising, making your business more productive, or writing a book?"

### Coupons for Children

- Important reason millionaires prepare detailed grocery lists: use discount coupons when buying groceries
- **Children and grandchildren observe processes, develop understanding of organized household**
- Envision typical kitchen table in home of Mr. and Mrs. American Millionaire
- Young children searching newspaper and coupon flyers for coupons Mom and Dad can use
- Reward for finding right coupons more than smile
- Acting out important lesson to help as adults
- Mom teaches children to search for coupons, also teaches basic organization
- Expanding alphabetized folder where stores coupons
- Teaches young children how to file and sort coupons
- Experience teaches price sensitivity, playing good defense
- Never too early to learn how to protect one's money
- Useful for children to help prepare shopping list
- Integrating coupons and sale items listed in advertisements
- Teaching young children how to organize, plan, integrate information will serve them well in future

### Planning and Organization

- Most self-made millionaires: planning and being well organized significant importance in economic success
- Guess what? Parents, especially mothers, were planners and organizers
- 4 out of 5 millionaires believe being well organized in dealing with big issues and planning major factors in overcoming fears and worries
- When major career, business, financial resources on line
- Think of young children developing shopping list by integrating verbalized needs with coupons
- Designing strategic plan for allocating financial resources properly, selecting suppliers
- Can ask them to prepare maps of supermarket interiors with item placement details
- Can check off needed items, give map and command to go shopping "like senior executives"

### Teaching Organization Early

- Even if don't save much money clipping coupons
- Even if preparing shopping list personally counterproductive
- Mere fact working with children in role of "instructor of planning" will benefit them someday
- Same applies to keeping strict calendar of household bills, family activities, household chores
- **Month-At-A-Glance brand ideal** for young and old alike—lots of room for kids to write
- As soon as children can ride bike, should be sensitized to benefits of planning system with monthly calendar
- Children should be instructed and required to keep own calendar
- Begin by listing chores, but should also include fun things like birthday parties, social events
- If demonstrate being organized and disciplined, children will imitate actions
- If disorganized in household environment, children may follow lead
- More effective to teach by example than talk about being disciplined and organized when not

### MBA Student Planning Exercise

- Taught course in strategic market planning requiring planning project
- Counted for 50% of students' grades
- Each student develop plan for actual company in market
- For most students, most difficult part: preparation of day-to-day schedule for each piece of plan to unfold
- Remedy: had each MBA student purchase Month-At-?-Glance
- Then had them start filling in processes by date in pencil
- Ink would never work—constantly making mistakes in planning process
- Had to place every single act, process, task on 3x5 inch cards (about 100-200 cards per plan)
- Each with action
- Required to integrate tasks with calendar
- Always asked students if ever done something like this before
- Far too many said no
- No matter how analytically intelligent, had little or no experience being truly organized
- Even without organizational skills or being trained to plan, received undergraduate degrees by doing exactly what professors told them to do
- When to study, read specific assignments, take tests
- **Not a lot of organizing necessary when someone else designs your plan**
- **Successful people are ones who do planning and organizing**

### Carl the Mentor

- Few days before Christmas, courier delivered large box with gift for wife and bottles of high-quality spirits
- Gifts sent by **Carl**, retiree previously CEO of two major corporations
- After listening to audiotape of talk at Downtown Atlanta Rotary Club, Carl telephoned author
- Asked for favor: making proposal to three school-aged grandkids
- All three required to read *The Millionaire Next Door*
- Then write short review of material
- Focusing on key point each grandchild learned from reading assignment
- Reviews evaluated, each given letter grade
- Grandchild with top grade gets cash prize of $500
- Two runners-up each receive $250
- If Granddad Carl did evaluating, might be criticized for "playing favorites"
- Asked impartial third party to grade three reviews
- Author agreed to act as judge

### The Book Review Results

- Reviews very well done
- Frankly amazed three grade school students could interpret and write so well
- Carl's granddaughter received A on review
- Other two very competitive, graded A-
- Carl is wise: knew *The Millionaire Next Door* could teach young grandchildren important facts
- About accumulating wealth and factors contributing to financial success
- Knew young people, even in first few years of grade school, can learn great deal about benefits of planning financial future

### Lessons for Parents

- Parents should train children how to plan
- Many young adults today have no clue how to prepare for future
- How can we expect them to become financially independent?
- **Must be mentors like Carl, role models and planning instructors for children and grandchildren**
- Also have to make learning fun, even immediately rewarding experience
- Carl knew this intuitively

### Professional vs. Amateur Plumbing

- Plumber who installed new water heater makes more per hour than you charge
- Was it mistake to hire him instead of doing yourself?
- In some states law requires only licensed plumber can install gas hot-water heaters
- Don't think you want to study plumbing and become licensed

### First Cost vs. Life-Cycle Cost

- Millionaires and those likely to become wealthy not "first-cost" sensitive
- They are **life-cycle-cost sensitive**
- "First cost": dollar cost savings if install water heater instead of using skilled plumber
- May have saved $150 in process, but figure very deceptive
- Plumber's quote included high-efficiency water heater
- Shopped and found low-priced (first cost) water heater with same gallon capacity
- Over projected life of heaters, plumber's will save more than $150 in operating costs
- Also estimated to last longer and heat water faster
- Over life of heater you install, no warranty on installation
- Could easily install incorrectly and burn out system
- Even worse, if not installed correctly, could escape and asphyxiate family
- **These issues relate to real cost savings when contrasting first cost versus life-cycle costs**
- **What value is your life and lives of family members? Priceless elements in equation**

### Trade-offs

- Other issue relates to trade-offs
- Cannot install water heater and simultaneously carry out assignments part of work
- Plumber still charges more per hour than you charge for hour of your time
- Could save by doing yourself
- But not thinking like millionaire, not thinking of life-cycle differences
- If decide to install water heater yourself:
  - Have to shop for unit (takes time and energy)
  - Could be using time and energy to enhance professional skills or study investments
  - Time could be using to shop for new clients
  - Acquiring one new client worth much more than $150
  - Have to study water-heater installation techniques, acquire proper tools
  - Whether rent or buy tools, takes time and money
  - How many other hot-water heaters will be installing during remainder of working life?
  - Bet never want to install another once suffered through first campaign to save $150
  - Why study plumbing if not going to be plumber?
- After all this, ask about actual dollars really saved
- In terms of life-cycle cost-benefit analysis, select option number two: **Call the plumber!**

### Defining Frugality

- Repeatedly told people millionaires frugal, but many think entire do-it-yourself concept defines frugality
- Millionaires frugal when frugality translates into real increases in economic productivity of household
- Webster's defines *frugal*: "characterized by or reflecting economy in expenditure of resources"
- Key word: *resources*, not just first-cost money or dollar resources
- Full-life-cycle resources associated with making purchase or other economic decision
- **Large majority of millionaires NOT do-it-yourselfers!**
- Reason: more productive to earn income from vocation and use it to hire professional painters, carpenters, plumbers

### The Cartoonist-Painter-Illustrator

- Asked high-income-producing cartoonist-painter-illustrator do-it-yourself question
- At time in his home, large English Tudor overlooking Hudson River Valley
- Looked out, noticed group of house painters setting up scaffolding
- Asked about cost of having such large home painted
- Price seemed so high felt compelled to ask: "You're a painter. Why not paint your own home?"
- Responded quickly, to point: could make more money doing job than cost of having crew do work
- Perhaps even more importantly said:

> "What if I fall off a ladder while painting the house? I could be killed or permanently disabled... never to be able to earn a good living."

- Cartoonist like most self-made millionaires—not penny wise and pound foolish

### Life-Cycle-Cost Sensitivity

- Things millionaires do to enhance economic productivity by reducing cost of operating household are life-cycle-cost sensitive
- Dangling on ladder could jeopardize ability to earn millions of future dollars in own vocation
- Much more likely to reinsulate home and have high-efficiency heating and air-conditioning systems installed
- Remember millionaires often live in same home for twenty years or more
- Over years, these changes will more than pay for their first costs

### To Write or to Commute?

- Use analysis of own resources as way of motivating self to write books
- How long to write *The Millionaire Next Door*?
- Wrote entire 477-page manuscript in about 180 days (43,200 minutes)
- Wrote on average four hours each and every day, about 240 minutes/day for 180 days
- May sound like whole lot of time and effort, but don't see it that way
- More than just 43,200 minutes
- Was 1.5 million symbols made by hand with No. 1 blue medium-point Papermate pen
- Looked at task way most productive people view work
- Motivate themselves by selecting from various alternatives for allocating time

- When contemplated writing *The Millionaire Next Door*, told self:

> "Tommy, it will take you less time to write this book than the time you spent sitting in traffic, over a period of thirteen years, commuting to and from the university where you once were employed as a professor."

- Mundane task of commuting took many more minutes of time and units of mental and physical energy than writing book
- Only have few hours each day to work at peak mental efficiency
- In case, about four hours maximum
- Had to decide if wanted to spend another 50,000 minutes in car or writing book
- What royalties paid for commuting?
- How much more productive will become careerwise by mastering stop-and-go driving?
- Unfortunately, millions of Americans waste mental and physical energy doing unproductive things

### Productivity Questions

- Good idea to allocate few minutes each month to enhancing productivity
- Ask yourself simple questions about allocation of time:
  - How much time will I spend doing each task during lifetime?
  - Is there some way can reduce this time allocation?
  - Are there better uses for my time than doing tasks have been doing habitually?
  - Is there some task can undertake that will pay benefits for rest of life?

### Build, Develop, or Rent

- Recently had conversation with **Mr. D.D. Thompson**, master builder of homes
- He and other family members do most construction on each home they build
- Family business produces quality product
- Mr. Thompson mentioned folks like author "have it easy"
- "We hammered or shot 250,000 nails in process of building that home. You folks just sit at desk."
- Enjoyed his comment
- Then told him "it's always greener on other side of one's vocation"

> "It took 1.5 million symbols [letters] made by my hand to complete my book manuscript. Plus it takes a lot of thought about the choice of letters."

- Though D.D. got kick out of comments, not sure got whole point
- Nailing takes effort, so does writing book, but very big difference
- What if letter placed on page eventually becomes part of best-selling book?
- Like each letter has some future income stream
- Once D.D. puts nail in piece of wood, gets paid once
- Has no inventory
- Gets paid only once; no royalties paid on nails

### The Developer vs. The Builder

- Even worse, D.D. builds homes for developer
- D.D. gets about 20% of profit; developer gets rest
- Like being ghostwriter who gets flat fee and no future royalties
- D.D. would be much better off building homes as own developer
- Perhaps even better: should build and rent small apartment properties
- Akin to having nails as annuity
- However, D.D. doesn't have capital to underwrite own construction
- Nor does he have discipline or forethought to develop savings plan enabling him to put away enough income to become developer someday

### The Nail Analogy

- Perhaps D.D. hasn't yet hammered enough nails
- Someday may grow really tired of spending all time and energy inserting nails that never pay dividends

### CPAs and Tax Returns

- Find many college graduates employed in positions involving inserting nails
- For example, take most CPAs in America
- Intelligent, hardworking professionals who prepare many tax returns each year
- But **cannot inventory tax returns**
- New task each year, year after year

### Software Success Stories

- Few CPAs went beyond inserting more nails each year
- Developed tax-related software programs
- Sold thousands and thousands of these programs
- Will sell even more in future
- Programs equivalent of goose that keeps laying royalties and related payments
- Great thing: these products can be inventoried
- They generate revenue without creators having to hammer one more custom tax return

### The Key Point

- **You are going to work hard hammering anyway**
- **Can hammer nails that will pay you once or pay you hundred times—up to you**
- If go through life like D.D., always be one nail, one payout
- If D.D. just spent few more hours each week building own spec house
- Perhaps with investor who put up money for materials for one-half share
- Would be in transition from treadmill existence of nailing to one of inventorying equivalents of nails, capital

### Professional Athletes

- People often ask opinion about high salaries of many professional ballplayers
- Believe they paid what they deserve
- Not at all envious of athletes who earn big incomes
- Many have very short careers
- Some realize goals, home runs, even touchdowns cannot be inventoried
- Even though receive many more dollars for hammering hits or blocking for quarterbacks
- Still same old nail game
- **Dollars earn for nails inserted today don't matter so much**
- **Real issue: how many future dollars your efforts today will pay**

### Team Owners and Agents

- Press loves to tell us how much some young ballplayer will make with contract
- But once playing days over, where is annuity? Dead as doornail
- **Really smart people in professional athletics: team owners and agents**
- These agents especially crafty group
- Don't have much specific talent themselves—don't run, kick, block, or score goals
- Don't sing or dance
- Yet they last and last
- What if you are one-in-a-million on football talent scale?
- Were high school All-American, first-team college All-American, first running back drafted in pros this year
- But blew out knee
- **Your agent, on other hand, has growing stable of your kind**
- **Grows business like people grow apple trees**
- Once in his orchard, keep producing for him
- When can no longer produce apples or hammer nails, remove dead or dying trunk from field
- Replacement apple tree inserted like interchangeable parts of machine

## Chapter 7 (continued): The Frugal and Productive Points

### The Points' Background

- **The Points**: retired couple living in fine four-bedroom home in one of Austin's nicer neighborhoods
- Net worth in high seven figures
- Frugal couple, very careful about how they spend money
- **Mrs. Point**: "My husband and I grew up during Depression, so we both are careful with our money"
- Although currently live in home worth $800,000, has paid for itself over years through appreciation

### Location Philosophy

- To Balance Sheet Affluent, careful means selecting home and neighborhood very carefully
- May mean paying more for home initially and paying higher property taxes
- Make correct selection, may do even better than having home pay for itself in real-dollar terms
- Mrs. Point expressed attitude:

> "I believe in living in the best section of the city... location, location, location... . I will do without fine cars, but insist on having the best home possible."

### Price Sensitivity Philosophy

- Points could purchase expensive automobiles and clothing, still remain in millionaire league
- But that's not their style
- Mrs. Point graciously outlined philosophy she and husband have always maintained
- Believe very important to be price sensitive with respect to products that lose all or most of initial value as soon as purchased
- In terms of dollar value, these items highly perishable
- Example: clothes
- If purchase expensive suit or dress today, how much worth at tomorrow's garage sale?
- Perhaps 5 or 10% or less of original purchase price
- Mrs. Point never
<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Chapter 7: The Economically Productive Household (continued)

### Mrs. Point's Clothing Strategy

**Mrs. Point** demonstrates millionaire consumption habits through her approach to clothing:
- Wears couture from designer brands (Yves Saint Laurent, Armani, Valentino, Oscar de la Renta, Gucci, Dior)
- Buys everything at Junior League shop — donated by wealthy families
- Has clothes altered instead of buying new when fit isn't perfect (40% of millionaires do this)
- Allocates savings to items that appreciate: medical stocks

> "I am mindful of the fact we live in a time of medical miracles... invest in stocks related to medicine." — Mrs. Point

- Points are health-conscious — Mrs. Point reads about health, attends seminars, studies medicines/drugs/patents
- Kills two birds with one stone: enhances physical health AND economic wealth through health research
- Careful with food purchases: clips/organizes coupons, does own cooking, exercises
- Confusing appearance to outsiders: expensive clothes but modest car spending, lives in expensive home but uses discount strategies
- Own land/mining operations and oil leases but don't broadcast their holdings

> "We have land... [and] mining operations and oil leases. We do not tell our friends about our holdings because many of those we associate with do not have as much as we do." — Mrs. Point

### Recycling: Tassels vs. Nikes

**70% of millionaires have shoes resoled** — understated because ~20% are retired and no longer wear "dress uniform" footwear

**Dress shoes/executive footwear:**
- Brands: Alden, Allen Edmonds, Johnson-Murphy
- Sold in specialty stores and upscale department stores
- Worn by senior executives, business owners, top physicians, attorneys, investment bankers, stockbrokers
- Cost $200-$300+ per pair
- Most buyers make decisions based on quality, not initial price
- **Quality-sensitive segment**: defines quality by life-cycle cost
- Author's Alden tassel loafers: 10+ years old, worn ~1,600 days, resoled twice ($50 each time)
- Total cost: $100 (initial) + $100 (resoles) + $20 (shoe trees) = $220
- **Life-cycle cost: 14 cents per wearing**

**Contrast: College student's Nikes/Adidases:**
- Goes through 6 pairs per year (walking on campus, running, touch football)
- 80-100 wears per pair
- $65-$85 per pair
- Even at best case (100 wears), life-cycle cost is 65 cents per wear

> "Cheap shoes wear you, you don't wear them!" — Survey respondent

> "Appearances can be very deceiving, and so can the first-cost or purchase price. For many products, life-cycle cost is a much more relevant criterion to use when shopping."

**Millionaires are built to last, support, and give comfort to one's physical foundation** — shoes are not inexpensive relative to other market offerings

### You Can Refinish Wood but Not Sawdust

**Millionaire furniture preferences:**
- Live in single-family homes of traditional design (well-built colonials, English Tudors)
- Interiors filled with traditional furniture, Early American most prevalent
- Not major consumers of modern furniture
- Prefer high-quality traditional furniture that never goes out of style
- Furniture made of **solid wood** — not sawdust glued together or thin veneers on particleboard
- Prefer solid wood or quality veneers on high-grade solid hardwoods

**Furniture brands millionaires own:**
- Baker Williamsburg
- Councill Craftsmen
- Henkel-Harris
- High-quality eighteenth-century and traditional furnishings

**Millionaires more likely to own antiques** — dealers confirm largest market segment is affluent people with traditional taste, more sensitive to quality than price variations

**Three sources of traditional furniture:**
1. High-quality reproductions made of real wood (from dealers)
2. High-grade antique furniture of traditional style
3. Intergenerational gifts and hand-me-downs

**Quality definition for millionaires:**
- Traditional design, well-constructed with real wood
- Will last a century or more
- Physical longevity important
- Traditional furniture remains in style and high demand among affluent

**High-quality furniture appreciates in value:**
- Ten- and twenty-year-old Henkel-Harris and Baker furniture sells for more than twice original purchase price
- Contrast: automobiles, $500 suits depreciate rapidly

**Millionaires are accumulators** — trait inherited from parents who were collectors
- Parents/grandparents held onto things with value
- Theme acted out by first-generation millionaires today
- Ancestors passed on possessions with lasting sentimental and monetary value
- Intuitively knew value of collecting/preserving items that appreciate
- Deliberately purchase furniture to pass on to younger generation tomorrow
- Definition of quality furniture: outlives normal adult life span, never loses appeal, probably appreciates

> "You can't saw sawdust; you can't even sand sawdust!" — Aphorism

**Quality furniture test:**
- Veneer on sawdust may last half a generation
- Leave water/coffee on top — veneer might separate from sawdust
- Can refinish high-quality furniture over and over again
- Don't buy new furniture soon as old has a scratch

**48% of millionaires have furniture refinished/reupholstered instead of buying new**

**Mrs. Claurice Rector** (multimillionaire):
- Refinishes and reupholsters "everything in the house"

> "Because it's just so much more convenient than searching... shopping [for new furniture] hour after hour, looking at high-priced nothings!" — Mrs. Rector

- Developed list of great refinishers and reupholsterers
- "I call. They send me swatches. They pick up. No malls; no hassles."
- Fabric selection easier than selecting new furniture
- Same family-owned shop reupholstered her favorites five times in thirty years

**Wall Street Journal article** (James R. Hagerty and Robert Berner, November 2, 1998):
- "On the couch, ever wonder why furniture shopping can be such a pain?"
- Documents difficulty finding furniture to purchase
- Buyer may wait weeks, even months for delivery
- Many styles and colors confusing
- One company offered 1.7 billion possible combinations of sofas and upholstered chairs
- Given variety, why not refinish and reupholster existing furniture?

### Looking for Clues

**Thirteen actions included in millionaire questionnaire** (Table 7-1) — developed from 200+ proposed actions/habits through focus groups and personal interviews

**Four major patterns emerged:**
1. **Extending the life cycle** (shoes resoled, furniture reupholstered, clothes mended)
2. **Reducing the monthly burdens** (raising thermostat, switching phone companies, paying off mortgage)
3. **Planning purchases** (never buying via phone solicitations, shopping lists, coupons, Consumer Reports research)
4. **Patronizing discount institutions** (warehouse stores like Sam's/Costco, discount brokerages)

**Pattern 1 respondents** (extending life cycle):
- 48% reupholster/refinish furniture
- Also tend to have shoes resoled/repaired and clothes mended/altered

**Pattern 2 respondents** (reducing monthly burdens):
- Responses independent of Pattern 1 items
- Switching phone companies not significantly associated with furniture reupholstering

**Two actions best represent millionaires' approach** to cost reduction and productivity enhancement:
1. Switching long-distance telephone companies
2. Having furniture reupholstered or refinished instead of buying new

### Economically Productive vs. Nonproductive Households

**Two millionaire samples:**
- **EPMs** (Economically Productive Millionaires): switch phone companies AND reupholster/refinish furniture
- **NEPMs** (Noneconomically Productive Millionaires): don't do either action

**EPMs are wealthy for several reasons:**
- Operate productive households (Table 7-2)
- Much more deliberate in home-purchasing approach
- Spend more time studying and planning investments

**NEPMs:**
- Earn so much income it's difficult not to become wealthy
- Can be millionaires without running efficient households

**Table 7-2 comparisons (EPM vs. NEPM percentages):**
- Shoes resoled: 81% vs. 55%
- Clothes mended/altered: 62% vs. 17%
- Raise thermostat in summer: 76% vs. 36%
- Pay off mortgage early: 57% vs. 44%
- Never buy via phone solicitations: 77% vs. 74%
- Develop shopping list before grocery shopping: 84% vs. 57%
- Use discount coupons for groceries: 65% vs. 33%
- Purchase top-rated appliances/vehicles: 58% vs. 31%
- Leave department stores quickly after purchase: 50% vs. 26%
- Buy household supplies at warehouse stores: 57% vs. 41%
- Use discount brokerage: 35% vs. 13%

### Mr. Oaks vs. Mr. O'Toole: The Pro Formas

**Mr. Oaks** (NEPM):
- Net worth: ~$7.5 million
- Annual realized income: $829,000
- Attorney working very long hours (60-80+ hour weeks)
- Focused, devoted to career
- Believes wealth will show up accordingly as long as he's tops in field
- Never took two key EPM actions (switching phone companies, reupholstering furniture)
- Views Table 7-2 actions as taking time/energy from high-paying career

> "Penny wise, pound foolish." — Mr. Oaks

- Operating costs in "penny category"
- "Pound category" = focusing intellect on winning $100 million settlement (income >$1 million next year)
- Little interest in variations in Consumer Reports for stoves/washing machines
- Just buys most expensive household appliances (theoretically the best)

**Mr. Oaks' success factors:**
- High IQ/superior intellect
- Attending top-rated college
- Graduating near/at top of class
- Well disciplined, working hard, getting along with people, being competitive

**Mr. O'Toole** (EPM):
- Net worth: ~$5 million
- Annual realized income: $544,000
- Entrepreneur in recycling/scrap metal business
- Lower net worth largely due to income differences
- Would have considerably less wealth without economically productive household
- He and wife operated household productively for 25+ years
- Had to do so or wouldn't have built recycling business

**Mr. O'Toole's success factors:**
- Investing in my own business
- Having a supportive spouse
- Willing to take financial risk given the right return

> "Living below my means." — Mr. O'Toole (very important success factor)

**53% of EPMs** rate "living below my means" as very important or important
**Only ~33% of NEPMs** rate this factor similarly

**EPM lifestyle differences:**
- Attend religious services
- Read the Bible
- Shop at Wal-Mart and Kmart
- Eat at McDonald's and/or Burger King
- Involved in do-it-yourself carpentry projects
- Shop via the Internet
- Mow their own lawns
- Garden
- Attend antique fairs/sales
- Consult with an investment adviser

**NEPM lifestyle differences:**
- Attend major league sporting events
- Attend fund-raising balls

**EPM shopping/investing integration:**
- Shop aggressively for homes
- Perceive home as part of investment portfolio
- Many NEPMs don't see it that way
- **81% of EPMs** (but only 52% of NEPMs) indicate "taking weeks, even months, to shop around for the very best deal overall" (Table 7-3)

### Home Purchase Strategies

**Median home purchase year: 1988**
- Since then, NEPM homes more than doubled in value
- O'Toole EPM group homes nearly tripled in value
- EPMs strongly believe economically productive to shop aggressively for homes
- Both groups bought fine homes in high-ranking established neighborhoods
- Both very wise to do so

**Mr. Oaks and NEPMs:**
- Took very little time shopping for best deal
- Bought fine home but paid for quality
- Graduated top college, top of class (undergraduate and law school)
- Immediately hired by top law firm
- Soon became partner
- 60-80+ hour work weeks not uncommon

**Table 7-3 home purchase actions (EPM vs. NEPM percentages):**
- Never paying initial asking price: 91% vs. 80%
- Willing to walk away from deal anytime: 84% vs. 77%
- Researching recent home sales prices in neighborhood: 89% vs. 72%
- Taking weeks/months to shop for best deal: 81% vs. 52%
- Never trying to purchase within short time span: 64% vs. 44%
- Seeking neighborhood with excellent public schools: 80% vs. 74%
- Purchasing easily affordable home: 66% vs. 53%
- Searching for low-maintenance energy-efficient home: 42% vs. 20%
- Searching for "bargain" home (foreclosure, divorce, estate sale): 45% vs. 14%
- Searching for neighborhood with reasonable property taxes: 39% vs. 21%
- Testing seller's price sensitivity with deeply discounted offer: 55% vs. 36%
- Asking realtor to reduce commission so seller can reduce price: 35% vs. 27%
- Purchasing building lot, then having contractor build: 27% vs. 25%
- Demanding builder/seller price at/near cost: 21% vs. 13%

**Oaks NEPM types:**
- Buy trophy homes in trophy neighborhoods
- Deal with cream of crop of real estate agents
- Tell agent: "Find me a trophy home within a week or month!"
- Home appreciated and will continue to do so

> "When faced with lack of time, it's better to buy a quality home at a high price than a nonquality home at a reduced price." — Rule from Oaks types

**Income/net worth comparison:**
- Oaks NEPMs: average annual realized income $830,000, average net worth $7,550,000
- O'Toole EPMs: average annual realized income $544,000, average net worth $5,200,000
- **Net worth accumulated per dollar of income:** EPMs $9.56, NEPMs $9.10
- Only ~5% difference — both groups productive in generating high incomes and net worth
- Each adopted wealth-building strategy suited to their abilities and interests

> "Never try to adopt an economic orientation that is incongruent with your abilities and aptitudes."

**~80% of both groups** suggest current vocation allows full use of aptitudes and abilities
- Both follow respective philosophies about enhancing household productivity

## Chapter 8: The Home

### Welcome to the Neighborhood

**Brian Abel** (prototypical millionaire):
- Lives in Balance Sheet Affluent (BA) neighborhood
- High concentrations of millionaires
- Nearly 80% of neighbors are millionaires
- Sharp contrast: only ~5% of ~100 million U.S. households are millionaires
- BA residents fully sixteen times more likely to be wealthy than national average

**Table 8-1: Year of Purchase of Current Home (N=733)**
- 1968: 10% purchased earlier, 90% later
- 1977: 25% earlier, 75% later
- 1986: 50% earlier, 50% later (median)
- 1993: 75% earlier, 25% later
- 1995: 90% earlier, 10% later
- 1996: 95% earlier, 5% later
- 1998: 99% earlier, 1% later

**Author's home:**
- Purchased ~12 years ago
- Purchase price: just under $560,000
- Would sell today for just under $1.4 million
- Increased wealth by ~$850,000 nominal ($70,000 per year)
- Same old-fashioned orientation: buy homes and hold for long periods
- Contrast: ~20% of American households move each year
- **53% haven't moved even once during past ten years**
- **24% moved just once in past ten years** (~80% were local moves)
- Very strong tendency to stay put

**Why millionaires seldom move:**
- Many are self-employed professionals or business owners/managers
- Moving away from clients, patients, customers, key suppliers would negatively impact enterprise productivity
- Preparing to move extremely disruptive, especially long-distance moves

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Chapter 8: The Millionaire Home (continued)

### Age and Location of Millionaire Homes

- **Median year of construction**: 1958 — two-thirds of millionaires live in homes built before 1973
- Only 1 in 20 lives in homes constructed in the last 5 years
- **BA neighborhoods were established decades ago** — well-established, not flashy or modern
- Homes are conservative in style: traditional colonials to English Tudors
- Only 1.7% live in homes with 8+ bedrooms; 52% have 4 or fewer bedrooms
- Only 2.3% have 8+ bathrooms; 46.6% have 3 bathrooms or less
- **Typical household**: married couples with 2-3 children

### Outstanding Mortgage Balances

- **39.9% have no mortgage at all**
- 50.1% have mortgages under $100,000
- Only 4.7% have mortgages of $1 million or more
- Millionaires typically buy homes only after accumulating wealth and establishing predictable cash flow

### Changes in the Neighborhood

**The Income Statement Affluent (IA) invasion**:
- BAs are selling, replaced by **Income Statement Affluent** (IA) types
- **"Stever"** (Mr. I. Steve Adams): 35-year-old stockbroker earning $500,000/year
- Bought home for $1.4 million (original owner paid under $400,000 fifteen years ago)
- Financed with $1.2 million jumbo mortgage
- Only 1 in 20 of his neighbors has $1M+ mortgage balance

> "Never borrow long-term with the prospects of short-term income."

**The IA trap**:
- High-performance sales professionals in their 30s-40s entering BA neighborhoods late in upswing
- Homes already doubled/tripled in value over past 10-12 years
- They wait until economy already in upswing — get paid commissions only after sales
- Real estate prices directly attached to economy changes
- **Sales professionals rarely in position to buy except during booms** — high income but low wealth (spend, borrow, borrow)

**Who bought during downturns (Dullsville economy)**:
- Owner/operator of funeral homes
- Scrap-metal dealer
- Owner/operator of parking lots
- Heart surgeon
- Senior partner with major law firm
- Owner/operator of waste-management business
- Senior partner of accounting firm

> "These BAs bought a home when they felt they were fully qualified to do so, one that will likely be affordable for them."

### Finding a "Lovely Home"

**"Lovely" homes sell quickly**:
- Excellent condition, nicely decorated, quality lot, fine neighborhood with good schools
- Often sell within days of listing, some before listing is public
- Some sold without professional real estate broker

**Smart buyer strategies**:
1. Not in hurry — serious but can wait
2. Want to be told immediately when "lovely" home listed in top-notch condition/right location

**Most millionaires never even tried to purchase a home in a short period of time**:
- They wait for the right "lovely" home to appear
- Never forced to accept substandard home
- Sharp contrast to employees who relocate under time pressure
- **More than half of millionaires haven't moved in 10+ years**
- **More than 1 in 5 living in same home purchased 25+ years ago**

**The "one owner, low mileage" model**:
- Prefer home with single owner over one with 8 different owners
- 8 owners leave 8 different traces of existence
- Example: Author's mother sold family home with only 2 owners in 45 years — no agent, 7% commission saved, sold for under $1,000 in miscellaneous costs
- Used local grapevine instead of real estate agent

**Alternative search methods**:
- **Billy Gilmore**: approached local developer with many condos — developer referred him to buyer list, found perfect match
- **Aggressive prospective buyers**: canvass neighborhoods, knock on doors (cold calls work for "lovely" homes owned by longtime residents beginning to feel need to sell)

### Proactive Searching

**Bargain shopping correlation**:
- **36% of decamillionaires** search for foreclosure/divorce settlement/estate sale homes
- **Only 18% of $1M-$2M millionaires** bargain shop this way
- **Wealthier millionaires are MORE deliberate**, not less
- Some search obituaries for early evidence of estate sales
- Example notice placed in mailboxes of lovely neighborhood:

> "I would like to purchase a home in your neighborhood. If you have any interest in possibly selling your home in the next year, contact me immediately at the phone number below."

### Guidelines from Millionaire Buyers

**Based on survey of 733 millionaires**:
- Most are self-made affluent who started at economic ground zero
- Home-buying is part of overall investment plan
- **Planning and studying investments is regular task for 9 in 10 millionaires**

**Guideline 1: Be willing to walk away**
- **82% felt they could say no to seller** (Table 8-6)
- For every 100 millionaires willing to walk, 456 never entered negotiation without willingness to walk
- Percentage correlated with net worth — **decamillionaires most likely to believe in "willingness to walk"**

**Guideline 2: Never pay initial asking price**
- **86% never pay asking price**
- For every 100 who paid asking price, 614 never paid it
- When true bargain presents itself, they pay asking price
- **Holly and Bill**: mid-forties, "live below your means" household — heard about trophy home through bridge party grapevine, knocked on door 2 hours later, recognized bargain price, put down cash deposit next morning
- Most millionaires play game of competition: select 2+ homes, negotiate prices
- **46% test price sensitivity** by making deeply discounted offers
- Some ask listing agent to reduce commission so seller can reduce price

**Aggressive negotiation by net worth**:
- **42% of decamillionaires** are aggressive commission/price negotiators
- **29% of $1M-$2M millionaires** negotiate this way
- **Positive correlation between net worth and aggressive negotiating**

**Guideline 3: Never try to purchase within short span of time**
- **54% never try to purchase home in short time**
- Haste makes waste — even millionaires admit to suboptimal decisions in past
- When forced to buy quickly, find best real estate agent possible:
  - Skilled, top-producing agent = walking, talking information database
  - Should forecast home values next year, 5 years, 10 years
  - Ask for references, contact previous clients

**The 10 and 65 rule**:
- About **10% of sales professionals account for more than 65%** of business generated by millionaire households
- Economically successful people patronize most productive CPAs, attorneys, physicians, real estate agents
- Millionaires have knack for finding great talent, keen sense of evaluating suppliers

**How to find top realtor**:
- Check Sunday newspaper real estate section
- Call managers of firms, ask for names of top guns
- Ask about accuracy of forecasts about home values
- Check previous clients
- Ask previous clients how well agent predicted the future

**Using legal network**:
- Patronize law firms with multiple offices in different cities
- Ask attorney to refer to associate in new city
- Ask associate for real estate agent referrals
- Law firms often have partners/associates who are real estate specialists

**Guideline 4: Search for foreclosure/divorce settlement/estate sale homes**
- **1 in 4 millionaires** search for "bargain" homes this way
- After 1987 stock market crash, **37% of home purchasers** searched for foreclosure group
- Attorneys more likely than any occupational group to search for bargain homes
- Not all distressed homes are physically distressed or lower priced
- **Cowboys of speculation** living in million-dollar homes — short-term income won't always cover long-term mortgage
- Credit-related sales of expensive homes even in good economic times

**Trophy Property Auction example** (Wall Street Journal, Feb 26, 1999):
- "Atlanta's Three Finest Mansions"
- "Bank orders these properties sold"
- Buckhead's most palatial mansion, opulent French Renaissance palace, 24K gold fixtures, opulent 22-room mansion, lagoon pool with waterfalls and spa

**Guideline 5: Building custom home**
- Only **27% have ever had home custom built**
- Most buy previously owned homes
- About 1 in 5 purchased spec house (built by builder/developer near completion)
- Various reasons millionaires averse to custom route

> "Building a home is like going into a business about which you know little or nothing. Not only are you going into business, often you are also going to work with a stranger."

**Advice for building custom**:
- Exploit patronage relationship with accountant and attorney
- Both professionals have knowledge about home-building contractors
- Want seasoned, astute professionals on your side
- Help put together long list of potential partners, prune to 2-3 qualified builders
- Leave budget, time constraints, construction plans in hands of CPA and lawyer

**Mr. Art Gifford case study** (accountant negotiating for neurosurgeon client):
- Builder wanted cost plus 15% fee on $1.1M home
- Builder wanted 5% sales commission on $300,000 lot
- Builder wanted to be the agent, owned the lot
- Proposed: $15,000 sales commission on lot + 15% of $1.1M fee = $165,000 builder fee
- Profit of $180,000 not including $100,000+ profit on lot alone

**Gifford's negotiation**:
- Told builder competing builders would build for 10%
- No sales commission on lot
- 10% fee on home more reasonable
- Negotiated down from 15% to 10% (saved client $70,000)

> "He is a client. He pays for our accounting and tax planning. Everything else is free. It's just part of our service. But I tell them, send me some business... tell your friends about us... referrals. That is how we do business."

**Builder became Gifford client** — referred several other wealthy clients
- Gifford did excellent job for both neurosurgeon and builder
- Knows how to win friends and clients, make them happy
- Never tries to gouge supplier or cut builder's profit to bone

> "But you never want to cut a deal so one-sided that the supplier, a builder or whoever, resents you. They want a fair deal. And remember, if you cut them to the bone, they will likely ignore your request to come back and repair things after the home is completed."

**Why bring in third parties**:
- Can save many dollars even at $5,000-$10,000/hour
- Skilled professionals can save 5-20x their fees by cutting reasonable deal
- Builders perform better when customer well represented by enlightened professionals
- Some suppliers have name for such customer: **"He's a businessman!"**
- People in business have more respect for businessmen/businesswomen than naive consumers

**Guideline 6: Always understand meaning of easily affordable home**

**58% purchase easily affordable homes** (Table 8-6)
- 4 in 10 millionaires (42%) have purchased homes not easy to afford
- Key is not only purchase price — major factor is **whether home will appreciate in value**
- Another consideration: **whether purchaser's income will significantly rise in real-dollar terms**

**Questions to ask**:
- Would proposed mortgage payments be difficult to make?
- What about tomorrow — will income rise or fall?
- Will value of proposed home increase substantially in near future?
- Answer honestly to avoid major financial mistake

**The $1.2M home trap**:
- What if you buy with just 10% down payment?
- After mortgage payments and household costs, zero dollars left over
- "Luxury-home-buying cowboys" convince themselves it's temporary:
  - My income will continue to rise each year
  - Home value will explode over next few years
  - I'm seasoned investor — 10% down is leverage deal
  - With $120,000 I control $1.1M of bank's money
  - Home will double in 5 years — $2.4M home after paying back mortgage = $1M+ profit

**Stanley's affordability test**:
1. Assume total annual realized income cut in half within a year of purchase
2. How long could you make mortgage/related payments with reduced income?
3. Assume investments decline in value by 50%
4. Could you still make ends meet for at least 5 years?
5. If answer is no, home is **not easily affordable**

**Cowboys vs. millionaires**:
- Hard to tell pro forma cowboy bad times follow good times
- Cowboys never had to earn income during bad times
- They think economy will boom indefinitely
- Sales professionals who earned $300,000 last year are the ones who overpay for homes in good times
- Judge ability to pay on single best income year

**Sales professionals have mixed feelings about good economic times**:
- Enjoy participating in prosperous economy
- Can produce even in bad times
- Like bad times because cowboys get eliminated, fewer competitors

**Home buyers**: Smart ones realize low interest rates + rapid growth of high-income households = increases in purchase price of homes
- **Price of expensive homes today = direct function of number of high-income-producing cowboys**
- Greatest number of cowboys born in 1957
- Today these early-forty-something buyers are everywhere million-dollar homes/mortgages exist in high concentrations
- **Watch what happens during next downturn — many trophy homes will be available**

### Green or Blue?

**Mr. Green** — higher net worth than others in income bracket:
- Extremely productive investor
- Fully integrated process of allocating investment dollars
- Doesn't limit investments to stock market
- Recognizes many other great opportunities
- **"Seeing business opportunities others did not see"**
- Has hunter's nose — can look around and recognize good investment opportunities

**Mr. Green on real estate**:
- Considerable knowledge of real estate market trends in his area

> "The Millionaire Next Door is a significant publication. My wife and I loved it, discussed it with friends and family and still compare ourselves to the norms. Where we differ is in making real estate a major investment opportunity. We are not wed to our house, but enjoy it. We'll sell it in the next year or two and expect a profit of $2.1 million or 125% before taxes. We'll build another, smaller house, pay off our relatively small (11%) mortgage, pay the taxes and still be up a million dollars. Welcome to Greenwich, Connecticut, in the '90s!!"

**The Greens**:
- Built current home 6 years ago at cost of $1.7M (including land)
- Worth $3.8M five years later (conservative estimate, could bring $4M+)
- Charter members of **Balance Sheet Affluent** group
- Bought and sold homes 4 times in 10 years, learned each time
- Buy something they feel will be easy to sell at good profit someday
- More homework/negotiating as buyers = better as sellers someday

**Contrast with the Blues** (**Income Statement Affluent Club**):
- Net worth about 2x annual realized income
- Could have difficult time living on it for more than few years
- On consumption treadmill — earn to spend, spend to earn
- Purchased $2.5M dream home with multimillion-dollar mortgage

**Table 8-7 comparison** (actions taken when purchasing home):
- Both purchased existing homes in adult lifetimes
- Most recently both had homes built for them
- **Mr. Green took 13 of 14 actions** attempting to get best possible deal
- **Mr. Blue took only 4 of 14 actions**

**Mr. Blue's approach**:
- Purchases homes he cannot easily afford
- Avoids testing seller's price sensitivity
- Impatient — believes in "buy now, pay later" philosophy
- IAs feel euphoric from sudden income upswings
- Spend in anticipation of becoming rich tomorrow
- Already consider themselves economic successes based on income statements
- Private banker approved his jumbo mortgage
- Counts income dollars he expects to earn over
<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## Continued: Home Buying Strategies (Mr. Green vs. Mr. Blue)

### Table 8-7: Comparison of Home-Buying Behaviors

**Balance Sheet Affluent (Mr. Green)**:
- Takes weeks/months to shop for best deal
- Seeks neighborhoods with excellent public schools
- Purchases easily affordable homes
- Searches for low-maintenance, energy-efficient homes
- Seeks "bargain" homes (foreclosure, divorce settlement, estate sale)
- Tests seller's price sensitivity with deeply discounted offers
- Asks realtor to reduce commission so seller can reduce price
- Demands builder price home at or near cost

**Income Statement Affluent (Mr. Blue)**:
- Wants to purchase quickly ("dog in heat")
- Does not prioritize public schools
- Does not seek easily affordable homes
- Does not search for energy efficiency
- Does not seek bargain properties
- Does not test price sensitivity
- Does not negotiate realtor commission
- Does not demand builder work at cost

> "Who really gets most of the 'real deals' in residential real estate? It's not the Blues, the IAs; it's the Greens, the BAs."

### The Cost of Custom Building

**Mr. Blue's approach**:
- Wanted unique, architecturally self-actualizing home
- Builder sensed he was "a dog in heat"
- Insensitive to price but sensitive to size, facade, style, Jacuzzi
- No firm cost figures from builder (cost-plus with 20% fee)
- Unique design means builder climbs learning curve on Mr. Blue's dime
- Eventually paid $2.5 million for home

**Mr. Green's approach**:
- Did homework, made reasonable estimates
- Boldly asked builder for actual cost data from recent builds
- Patient, not in a rush
- Insisted realtor reduce commission to lower seller's price
- Competition among sellers works in his favor
- Paid $1.7 million for comparable quality home

> "I never, ever try to purchase a home or lot within a short span of time. I'm always looking for a great opportunity. I can inventory a building lot for years before I decide to build a home on it."

> "I take weeks, months, even a year or more to shop around for the very best deal overall. I'm never in a hurry."

> "I'm always searching for a 'bargain' home or lot that may be part of a foreclosure, divorce settlement, or estate sale."

### First-Cost vs. Life-Cycle Cost Sensitivity

**First cost**: Initial purchase price for lots, homes, construction

**Life-cycle cost**: Direct and indirect costs over time

- **Mr. Green**: Life-cycle sensitive, not first-cost sensitive
- **Mr. Blue**: Relatively more first-cost sensitive, but overall less sensitive on both dimensions
- IAs often delude themselves when making home-buying decisions by painting rosy picture of both first and life-cycle costs

### The Public School Factor

**Mr. Blue's mistake**:
- Moved to neighborhood without researching schools
- Discovered public schools were subpar
- Children couldn't gain admission to quality colleges
- Added $33,000/year private school tuition to life-cycle costs

**Millionaire survey findings**:
- 79% stated important decision criteria was "seeking a neighborhood that has excellent public schools"
- Only 26% searched for neighborhoods with reasonable property taxes
- Most BAs realize trade-offs: higher property taxes = quality public schools
- Low tax rates in Mr. Green's mind equate with low-quality schools

**Mr. Green's investment success**:
- $1.7 million home more than doubled in value in under 6 years
- Trophy home in trophy neighborhood
- Area and home very desirable to affluent buyers
- Risk isn't buying expensive home in good area—risk is buying cheaper home in non-trophy neighborhood with subpar schools

## The Hunter's Nose

### Stanley's Personal Experience (Early 1980s)

**Context**:
- Interest rates near 20%
- Money-market funds paying near 20% returns
- People exiting stock market for guaranteed cash returns
- Residential real estate market dampened
- Sellers begging to unload homes

**Stanley's situation**:
- Long commute (30 miles) to downtown
- Bottleneck at two-lane bridge
- High interest rates made him hesitant to buy closer

**The multimillionaire focus group**:
- 10 multimillionaires, all from New York metro area
- All business owners, first-generation affluent
- Repeatedly mentioned "Atlanta, Atlanta" as land of opportunity
- Asked if Stanley was buying real estate in Atlanta
- Confused Stanley—none were real estate professionals

**Mr. Brown's advice**:

> "Tom, this is the best time to buy! Smart people—they don't always need to borrow. Have you considered buying? Do you have enough cash to buy a building lot in a quality area? Then do it. Do it now. Never follow the crowd. I'll wager there's plenty of property for sale. Look in the classifieds... Call a few banks that have foreclosures."

### Stanley's Purchase Decision

- Bought one-acre lot on former plantation for $29,500
- Two years earlier, similar lots sold for double that price
- During next upswing, comparable lots sold for $100,000

**Who was selling?**:
1. Builders suffering under bad economic conditions with bills to pay
2. Income Statement Affluent who bought lots during boom times to build dream homes, paid premium prices in seller's market

**Balance Sheet Affluent behavior**:
- Bought building lots through economic ups and downs
- Some held lots for years waiting for market bottom
- Built homes when builders "delighted to build at or near cost for just the work"
- "Killed two birds with one stone"—productivity hallmark

### Real Estate as Part of One's Portfolio

> "There is a strong correlation between net worth and the proportion of one's wealth that is invested in real estate."

**Multimillionaire investment habits**:
- Most had chunk of wealth in conventional financial investments
- Much more than stocks and bonds
- Astute private investors owned:
  - Industrial real estate
  - Office complex
  - Factory
  - Medical science complex
  - Rental property
  - Vacation rental property
  - Shopping centers

### Case Study: Alvin (The Hunter's Nose)

- High school dropout, distribution business owner worth $30+ million
- Lived in fine neighborhood outside NYC
- Purchased home after becoming multimillionaire during buyer's market
- Home appreciated threefold in fifteen years
- Noticed pockets of opportunity in own neighborhood

**First target**:
- Home near his, unoccupied almost a year due to divorce
- Neglected during that time
- Purchased at bargain, cleaned, painted, improved
- Rented to relative, then sold when market turned
- Put home up for sale at 20% over appraisal price

**Alvin's selling strategy**:
- Balance Sheet Affluent—sells to earn profit, not from dire need
- Priced property knowing market was rising
- Value increased each day
- Waited for one buyer willing to pay top dollar
- Sold near asking price, grossed over 50% on investment

> "Doing what Alvin did is not for most people... if he was at or near ground zero he would never have contemplated buying 'investment' homes."

**Growing BA trend**:
- Pricing own homes in "Trophyville"
- Waiting for the price they name
- Sell in seller's markets, buy in buyer's markets
- Buy bargains in own or adjacent neighborhoods
- Some take residence in bargain-priced trophies
- Others use purely as investment vehicles

## Home Game/Away Game

### The Home Game Advantage

**Area-specific expertise**:
- BAs becoming experts in neighborhoods they know well
- Take opportunities to enhance net worth
- Not unusual to find affluent household that traded up/down to another home several times within same or adjacent community

**Discovery method**:
- Many homes discovered not in classifieds but at bridge parties, PTA meetings
- **Home game**: home team advantage, playing on own field
- Home crowd has home-field advantage over prospective buyers who know less about neighborhood
- Quick two-day house-shopping visits related to employment changes put buyers at disadvantage

### Winning the Away Games

**Mr. and Mrs. Dye**:
- Employee who worked for two major corporations
- Much-traveled career
- Last six long-distance moves: made considerable profit every time
- Locations: Chicago, Houston, Orlando
- Always bought low, sold high

**Strategy**:
- Transformed into members of home team in each new location
- Never panic when buying or selling
- Very patient, have plan and goals
- Took six months to sell old home and make purchase decision in most recent move

**Recent move details**:
- Employer offered to buy each of six homes at good, fair market price
- Mr. Dye turned down each offer
- Wise decision—couple sold homes at 15%+ more than fair market value

> "Cleanliness is next to godliness!"

**Home maintenance**:
- Homes always spotless inside and out
- Don't spruce up just before selling
- Always in turnkey condition
- Only buy homes in excellent condition
- Go beyond excellence with up-to-date color and decor
- Only buy homes they can sell later at profit

### The Ideal Buyer for the Dyes

**Profile of buyer**:
- Two-career couple employed in computer industry
- Moved frequently
- Both in late thirties
- Demanding, high-paying jobs with lots of travel
- No interest in restoring or redecorating
- Wanted turnkey home immediately
- Paid premium (20%+ above market) for above-excellent condition
- Not interested in new homes (require new lawns, decorating, drapes)
- All about work, aggressively pursuing careers and big incomes
- Time and effort outside vocations translated into big negatives

**Couple was IA playing away game**:
- Allocated weekend to find suitable home
- Knew nothing about real estate market in new city
- Insensitive to price variations among competing homes
- Significantly less sensitive to price among homes suitable to them
- Paid largest percent premium over market value in subdivision history (nearly 33%)
- Seventeen months later sold same home for 85% of what they paid
- Home not in above-excellent condition when they sold
- Employers subsidized part of loss

### Planning for Relocation Success

> "Always have a plan in place before you or your employer decide that it's time to change addresses."

**Key strategies**:
1. Keep home in excellent condition
2. Stay in touch with top real estate agents every six months
3. Periodically note names of residential real estate superstars
4. Ask business associates for referrals and canvas real estate firms
5. Interview top agents about market conditions
6. Ask how many recent sales came from clients moving into area
7. Ask about average time clients allocated to searching before purchasing

**Finding top agents in new locations**:
- Best agents often have close relationships with top firms in major industries
- When major company hiring important out-of-state employee, firm wants smooth transition
- Plan should include familiarizing with agents who have excellent track records making inbound executives happy
- Many top agents work especially hard to sell homes they also list

> "I take no pleasure in saying that it's often a bad mistake to hire a neighbor, friend, or even a relative as a real estate agent. Business is business, and today more than ever before, you can ill afford to be represented by someone other than a highly productive and completely professional real estate expert."

### Three Types of Real Estate Agents

1. **Listers**: Those who acquire listings
2. **Sellers**: Those who sell
3. **Sales and Marketing Commandos**: Great at both acquiring listings and selling (ESP types)

**Exceptional performers**:
- Some aggressive listers built tremendous goodwill with other brokers
- Other brokers take special note when their name is on For Sale sign
- Most agents are not sales and marketing commandos
- Much easier to encourage neighbor/friend/relative to list with them
- Much more difficult to sell (most sales made to strangers)
- Best real estate agents both list and sell

## Case Study: Connie Glenn (ESP Real Estate Agent)

**Context**:
- Stanley needed to sell house when mortgage rate near 20%
- Buyer's market in Atlanta
- Made mistake of asking friend/neighbor/part-time agent first
- After two months: no offers, no nibbles, very little traffic

**Hiring Connie**:
- Called manager of largest real estate agency in Atlanta
- Asked for "very, very best agent... not the best in Dunwoody or Roswell. I want the best horse in your stable."
- Connie and assistant appeared soon after
- Traffic increased overnight
- House sold within month for 95% of asking price

**Connie's success**:
- Market difficult, home was cedar (discolors, needs periodic cleaning)
- Found executive from lumber industry who loved cedar
- "After all, Tom, what would you expect a lumber expert to live in—a brick colonial? It would be bad for his reputation and the image of the lumber company."

> "My experience with Connie taught me something about marketing. If you want to avoid losing money on your real estate dealings, call an ESP." (Thomas J. Stanley, *Marketing to the Affluent*, Homewood, IL: Dow-Jones Irwin, 1988, pp. 40-41)

**Connie's qualities**:
- Established reputation as top gun by "aggressively seeking listings of homes that others were unable to sell"
- Recognized every real estate market has particular characteristics
- Hunter's nose and determination of bulldog

**Georgia as "wood state"**:
- Top-five state in lumber production
- Vast tracts of forests
- Many firms in lumber industry have presence
- Knowing this, Connie developed contacts and reputation in wood and key industries

**Value of Connie Glenn types over career**:
- Five or six moves: net much more money from her expertise at selling
- After five or six moves: net more than full purchase price of first home
- Can account for hundreds of thousands of dollars in pocket—even millions over millionaire's life cycle

## Plan or Panic?

**Time parameters for relocation**:
- Don't panic when finding you'll be moving
- Anticipate possibility as employee
- Decide beforehand how long you'll be willing to search
- Dyes willing to wait up to six months to find home and sell current home
- Not for everyone

**Mr. Dye's employer generosity**:
- Paid all moving expenses
- Included rent incurred while couple searched

**Value of renting temporarily**:
- Few months' rent not a lot to pay to acquire appreciating home that's easy to resell
- Transforms from visiting team member to home team member

## No Such Thing as a Perfect Prediction

**Due diligence before purchasing**:
- Study the clues before considering purchase
- Ask why owner is selling (may not reveal neighbor's home becoming eyesore)
- Easy to overlook condition of surrounding homes
- Slow down, walk neighborhood, closely examine other homes
- What percentage need exterior work? New gutters? Lawn/shrub maintenance?
- Who are prospective neighbors? What do they do for living?

**Asking the real estate agent**:
- Trends in neighborhood
- Are home values rising, flat, or declining?
- Agent will be impressed with sensitivity and may be more candid

**Walking and talking to neighbors**:
- Knock on doors, talk to potential neighbors
- Look them over carefully
- Ask about schools, what they enjoy or dislike

**Warning signs**:
- Home values not keeping pace with nearby neighborhoods
- One in five homes need exterior paint
- Homeowner next door recently lost job as corporate middle manager
- Home needs exterior work

**Neighborhood decline**:
- Many neighborhoods decline in real-dollar-value terms, even in affluent areas
- Often impossible to predict whether neighborhood will decline or appreciate
- Especially true in brand-new or near-new subdivisions

**Author's rule**:
- Look carefully at homes in well-established neighborhood
- If more than one in five clearly needs painting or landscaping, avoid risk of buying there

## Build or Buy

**Survey findings**:
- Only about one in four (27%) millionaires ever had home built for them
- Includes all categories: primary homes, second homes, summer homes, winter homes
- Proportion who build increases with net worth level
- However, only 35% of decamillionaires ever had home built

**John's reaction**:
- Shocked by revelations
- Thought millionaires built to save money
- After seeing data, developed new thesis:

> "Now I got it. Millionaires don't need to save money building. But I'm not [rich]. That's why I want to build."

### The "I'll Save Money" Myth

**Why majority of millionaires never build homes**:
- Believe some benefits of building vs. buying
- Feel benefits don't offset marginal costs of time, energy, and other resources

**Popular belief vs. reality**:
- Wealthy people perceived to have need for custom products
- Make no mistake: there are some who express themselves this way
- Home as extension of who they are and what they wish to tell people
- Resale won't satisfy needs
- Small segment—fewer than one in ten

**Very small segment (fewer than 15 in 100)**:
- Decide to build primary residence to save money
- Very sensitive to cost differences of building vs. buying
- Act as if lower premium on value of their time
- Believe financially beneficial to spend more time on building process than working at primary vocation
- Most price-sensitive bargain shoppers of all millionaires
- Build because they think they'll save a lot

**Example mindset**:
- Look at existing home priced at $400,000
- Say to themselves: "I could have it built for $300,000, including the lot."

**Opportunity cost consideration**:
- Young attorney in position with great advancement prospects
- Income jump from $78,000/year to over $300,000 if making partner
- Should you take time to have home built?
- Hundreds of phone calls from builder, suppliers, subcontractors during 6-10 month period?
- Valuable to visit construction site every few days?

**Competition scenario**:
- Two young attorneys competing for one partner opening
- Bet on Mr. Build or Mr. Buy?
- Even if Mr. Build saved $100,000 off comparable home, spent so much time and energy on project it took edge off performance
- Did not make partner

### Good Legal Advice

**Variation among occupational groups**:
- Very wide variation in building vs. buying behavior
- Some occupational categories significantly more likely to build
- As a rule, wealthy attorneys averse to building


<!-- pp. 341-360 -->

## Chapter 8 (continued): The Homes of Millionaires

### Why Attorneys Don't Build Custom Homes

- **88% of millionaire attorneys** have never built a custom home
- Two main reasons attorneys avoid building:
  - **Productivity trade-off**: 80% earn $200,000+ annually, half earn $400,000+. Legal services cannot be inventoried — time spent on construction = lost billable hours
  - **Legal and economic risks**: Even with the best builder, disasters happen (death, disability, project abandonment). Who completes the home? What happens to advance payments?

### Builder Horror Stories

Real examples from millionaires who built custom homes:

- Wallpaper installed **upside down** in 18-foot foyer. Sub unpaid by builder, placed lien on home, blocked mortgage approval. Required lawyer and bond.
- Basement slab poured after torrential rain on steep hillside — **wet concrete broke loose**, rushed downhill. Contractor blamed owner for insisting on full basement.
- Builder assured "no rocks underground," then hit **granite** first day. Needed 200+ sticks of explosives, over a week of blasting. Cost **$10,000+ just to remove rock**.
- Worker knocked hole in foundation for pipes, filled with **wrong mortar**. Cracked nine-foot foundation top to bottom. "Still cracked... still leaks when it rains."
- Subcontractor (framer) **overbilled** builder, who passed bills to owner. When questioned, builder got angry.
- Builder promised framing "Wednesday" — meant **two months** from now, not next week.
- Builder said fireplace would be done "as soon as rock mason comes back to work." **Builder was his own rock mason**.
- Carpet installers **stapled through floor sensors** for alarm system. Multiple false alarms, police visits.
- Contractor hired rookie with bulldozer for grading — **leveled every tree** in 100' × 200' backyard. "Once filled with hardwoods."
- At completion: **360 suppliers** to contact. Probably spoke to half during project.
- Attorney's stack of **client complaints** about builders: "very expensive homes... very angry people."

### Stanley's Advice for Custom Home Building

- **Consult your attorney** before considering custom home
- Large law firms = advantage: 50-100 lawyers likely include 5-10 who built homes, some satisfied with builders or who hired "high-grade" builders
- Let attorney handle **all legal issues** in building
- Never sign construction contract without attorney input — **better yet, have attorney write it**
- Don't go "out of control" on customization. Every unique element = delays, disappointments, cost overruns. **More productive to avoid fully customized dwelling**.

## Chapter 8 (continued): More Than the Purchase Price

### Case Study: Mr. Adam and His Son Nate

**Mr. Adam** ($20M net worth) wants to buy son **Nate** (age 30) a $425,000 home.

**Nate's situation:**
- Recently started career in insurance/investment business
- Income: ~$30,000/year
- Wife: part-time hair stylist, wants to quit and be full-time housewife
- **Combined household income: ~$40,000** (average for all US households)

**The daughter-in-law instigated** the request:
- She likes **Legacy Estates** (north county) — has tennis and golf club
- Wants to be full-time housewife and play tennis

**Stanley's point:** $425,000 purchase price is only the beginning. The **operating costs and lifestyle** of a $425,000 neighborhood are what matter.

### The Hidden Costs

**Property taxes alone:** $7,600-$8,000/year
- After income taxes and Social Security: household takes home <$35,000 of $40,000 gross
- Taxes = **$7,600 over $35,000 = 22% of income** minimum

**National context:**
- $425,000 home = **more than 3× the average single-family home** in America
- People who buy $425,000 homes have incomes **more than 3× the average**

**Typical millionaire in $277,640 home:**
- Total realized annual income: **~$145,000**
- Nate and wife income: **$40,000 = 27.6% of millionaire average**

### The Demographic Reality

Neighborhoods with $425,000 homes:
- Typical household annual income: **more than 3× Nate's income**
- Most earners: executives, professionals, successful business owners (six-digit incomes)

**Nate would be extraordinary** if he lived in $425,000 neighborhood and fit in — but **extraordinary at spending**, not earning.

### IRS Data: Home Values by Net Worth (Table 8-8)

**Average home values for millionaires nationwide:**
- **$1-2.5M net worth:** $220,796 home
- **$2.5-5M net worth:** $354,043 home
- **$5-10M net worth:** $545,499 home
- **$10-20M net worth:** $779,444 home
- **$20M+ net worth:** $1,073,980 home
- **All millionaires ($1M+):** $277,640 home

**Nate is proposing a home more expensive than those owned by most millionaires.**

Source: MRI database 1999 and IRS estimates 1996.

### The Defensive Memo

**Stanley's suggested memo format** for affluent parents facing EOC (Economic Outpatient Care) pressure:

**MEMORANDUM**

TO: Nates and Natettes
FROM: Affluent Parents
RE: Your Request for Subsidized Housing (a $425,000 home gift)

**Key points:**

1. **Average millionaire** (net worth <$3M) lives in home valued at **$277,640**. You are not a millionaire. Why do you need a $425,000 home? You're proposing a home **153.1% more valuable** than typical millionaire's home.

2. **Typical millionaire** in $277,640 home has total realized annual income of **~$145,000**. Your current income: **$40,000 = 27.6%** of millionaire average. Why not consider a home valued at **27.6% of typical millionaire's home ($277,640)? = roughly $77,000**.

3. **Starter homes** within 20-30 miles in that price range exist. Good fit for $40,000 income bracket. If you insist on more expensive home, **we will subsidize only up to $77,000**. You pay additional cost. You may wish to postpone purchase until you acquire more capital.

### Why the Memo Matters

**Mr. Adam is in denial stage.** Believes once he hands over $425,000 home, Nate will be self-sufficient.

Reality: **Even with 2× their current income, they'd struggle to support themselves** in that environment.

**What will happen:**
- Nate and wife will **require constant EOC doses** from Mr. Adam
- Subsidies **dampen ambition** and development of strong self-image
- Mr. Adam feels his son will be "more ambitious, more self-confident if only" he lives among ambitious high-income achievers
- **But ambition and confidence are not contracted like a disease** — living near successful people doesn't automatically transform you into a productive person

**Expenditures data** (Table 8-9):
- Households with **$90,000+ income** spend **$80,645 total** annually
- **More than 2× Nate's and wife's current income**

### The Full Cost of Accepting EOC

**Case example:** Married couple (mid-40s) wanted to build **$570,000 home**, short on capital.

Husband asked **wealthy retired parents** for subsidy. Parents lived in Ohio, interested in moving closer to son's family. Atlanta appealed, but they'd never shopped for homes there.

**Parents' response:**
- Sure, you may be worth several million dollars, but you're retired
- Big income-earning years behind you
- Deserve to enjoy remaining golden years **without providing adult, college-educated children with hundreds of thousands of dollars**

**How to say no without hurting feelings?**

Couple considered responses, then hit on solution:
- Told son they'd provide subsidy, **but with one condition**
- Architect must make changes to home plans

**The condition:**
- Entire basement area converted to **apartment**: 2 bedrooms, full kitchen, 1.5 baths, den, wall-to-wall carpet, full appliances
- When parents finally move from Ohio, they could **move in with son's family, rent-free**
- Move could be sooner if one parent died or became disabled

**Son turned down the deal.** Hard to believe.

## Chapter 9: The Lifestyles of Millionaires: Real vs. Imagined

### Mr. RRP: The Ultimate Consumer

**Mr. RRP** (Regional Radio Personality) — "ultimate consumer."

Called Stanley for interview. Very persuasive, great telephone voice. Show rated #2 or #3 in broadcast area.

Stanley arrived an hour before airtime. **RRP got down to business immediately:**
- Contract up for renewal
- Spent considerable time negotiating with station's senior executive
- Strongly believed he'd save money by being his own manager (no agent)
- **Not represented by skilled negotiator**

**Within 10 minutes, RRP revealed his financial problems:**
- **$30,000+ credit card debt** = over $7,000 annual interest payments
- Not unusual for him — had this balance outstanding for many years, often higher

**RRP's income and net worth:**
- Earns **$100,000+ annually** (top 7% of income-producing individuals in America)
- **Negative net worth**

**How is this possible?**
- Single, rents home, leases automobiles
- No large family, no medical expenses for elderly relative, no education loans

**Answer: He is a hyperspender.**
- Believes one must spend a lot of money to enjoy life
- **In his mind and habits** — buying products/services has direct influence on happiness
- Can only be happy if income increases
- Becoming progressively worried about not being happy — **only way to be happy is to spend into "Enjoyment World"**

**RRP told his boss:**
- In debt, unable to make ends meet
- Went beyond outlining financial problems

**RRP's situation:**
- Needs a job, has **less than zero wealth**
- At mercy of employer, not the other way around
- Makes no difference that he owns dozen watches, two expensive automobiles, bar tabs at top singles bars, dines at fine restaurants, every type of recreational equipment
- **Has no wealth. At economic razor's edge. Cannot live more than a month or two without a paycheck.**

### RRP's Negotiating Disaster

RRP went **one step beyond** telling boss about economic situation.

**Likely employer response:**
- Not giving him a raise
- Might start looking to replace him
- Key employee **possessed by possessions and consumption cannot be productive**
- Having negative net worth can be **distracting, dampening effect on job performance**

**RRP forgot something about life:**
- One does **not** have to buy products and services to get a lot out of it
- RRP's lifestyle = shopping and consuming
- To him, impossible to enjoy summer without Jet Ski or two (perhaps on credit)
- Can't have fun without spending hours downing "premier label" scotch at $7/hit at trendy bar

**RRP is:**
- Overspent, overfed, overdressed, overliquored, overentertainеd, overindulgent in general
- Everything outside working and sleeping **costs a lot of money**
- Focus is Mr. RRP and Mr. RRP's problems
- Believes he can **spend his way into "Club of Happiness"**

### RRP vs. Millionaire Lifestyle

**RRP's lifestyle very different** from activities and interests of most millionaires.

**RRP thinks millionaires are even more indulgent** than he is — completely wrong.

**Moderation in consumption and healthy, disciplined lifestyle = hallmarks of affluent in America.**

Are your lifestyle habits **congruent with becoming more productive?**
- For most with millionaire mind: **yes**
- For Mr. RRP: **no!**

Keep Mr. RRP and his lifestyle in mind when reviewing millionaire activities in this chapter.

### Real vs. Imagined Millionaire Activities

**Survey of 733 millionaires:** lifestyle activities during past month.

**Context — the typical millionaire:**
- Among most productive business owners, senior corporate executives, physicians, attorneys in America
- Live in many better-quality neighborhoods
- Homes average **$1.4 million**
- Well educated — ~**90% college graduates**
- Average annual realized income: **$600,000+**
- Net worth: **high seven figures**

**Outside of working, what do they do?**

If you think all millionaires are workaholics: **wrong**. Most have well-balanced life. Activities and interests **not as flashy** as Hollywood/popular press would have us believe.

**Common misconceptions:**
- Would attending religious services be too common for self-made millionaires? (They only believe in themselves and ability to generate income/wealth) — **Wrong**
- Would millionaires be more likely shopping at Brooks Brothers or Saks than eating at Burger King or McDonald's? — **Try again**

**One thing to remember:**
- Millionaires extraordinarily successful at producing high incomes and accumulating wealth
- Activities directly related to these (planning investments, consulting with advisers) **make up large part of activity lists**
- In many other lifestyle aspects, millionaires **anything but extraordinary**
- **Few habits set them apart** from most of us

**When people ask about millionaire lifestyles, short answer:**

> **"A cheap date!"**

### Top Millionaire Activities (Table 9-1)

**27 lifestyle activities ranked by participation** (past 30 days):

**Top 5:**
1. **Socializing with children/grandchildren (93%)**
2. **Entertaining close friends (88%)**
3. **Planning investments (86%)**
4. **Studying investment opportunities (78%)**
5. **Taking photographs (67%)**

**Other notable activities:**
- Watching children/grandchildren play sports (61%)
- Consulting with investment adviser (59%)
- Studying art/investments (53%)
- **Attending religious services (52%)**
- Jogging/running (47%)
- **Praying (47%)**
- **Eating at McDonald's and/or Burger King (46%)**
- Playing golf (45%)
- Attending lectures (43%)

**Lower participation:**
- Shopping at Saks Fifth Avenue (26%)
- Shopping at Brooks Brothers (19%)
- Shopping at Sears/J.C. Penney (17%)
- Off-roading via 4×4 (5%)

### Key Insights from Activity Rankings

**Family and friends dominate** — top two activities are people-focused, not consumption-focused.

**Religious activities significant:**
- Attending religious services: **52% (rank 9)**
- Praying: **47% (rank 10)**
- Bible/devotional reading: **22% (rank 23)**
- Attending religious events: **37% (rank 15)**

**Investment activities cluster high:**
- Planning investments (86%, rank 3)
- Studying investment opportunities (78%, rank 4)
- Consulting with investment adviser (59%, rank 7)
- Studying art/investments (53%, rank 8)

**Low-cost activities common:**
- Eating at McDonald's/Burger King: **46% (rank 12)**
- Shopping at Wal-Mart/Kmart: **31% (rank 17)**
- Do-it-yourself carpentry: **31% (rank 17)**

**Upscale shopping relatively rare:**
- Saks Fifth Avenue: 26% (rank 20)
- Brooks Brothers: 19% (rank 25)

**Message: Millionaires don't depend on consumer goods to enjoy life.**

Pleasures and self-satisfaction come from:
- Families
- Friends
- Religion
- Financial independence
- Physical fitness
- Perhaps a bit of golf

**Nothing more pitiful** than person who has no close friends, no loving family, yet owns millions in consumer goods.

**People like that = very small segment of millionaire population.**

**Strong positive correlation** between number of people-related lifestyle activities and level of net worth.

> "It's just as a multimillionaire once told me. He coached his daughter's softball team for several years. Although not premeditated, he met many successful parents who were business owners. Some ultimately became his clients. It doesn't matter if you're marketing commercial real estate or legal services — **it helps to be active, to interact with other successful people.**"

<!-- pp. 361-380 -->

## Chapter 9: The Lifestyles of Millionaires (continued)

### More Than Just Watching

- **Decamillionaires are nearly twice as likely to play golf than high-income-producing nonmillionaires**
- Golf ranks 13th overall in millionaire activities (only 45% played in past month)
- **Watching children/grandchildren play sports: 61%** — far higher than playing golf (45%) or tennis (23%)
- Millionaires value watching children's sports more than their own recreation
- Most surveyed played competitive sports in youth (JV football, freshman softball)
- Benefits: enhanced competitive nature, learned teamwork, exercise habits carried into adulthood
- **Strong positive correlation between net worth and frequency of watching children play sports**

### The "Cheap Date" Concept

- **Time control is the hallmark of being wealthy** — discretion over how you allocate time
- Affluent have more discretion over schedules than nonaffluent
- Most millionaires are self-employed business owners or professionals who make their own schedules
- Blue-collar workers paid by hour/pieces produced — work takes priority during game time
- Economic success = direct function of defining one's own allocation of time and motion

> "Since you can't be in two places at one time, if you're watching your kids play ball you can't be shopping at Brooks Brothers or Saks."

### Table 9-3: "Cheap Date" vs. Costly Activities

**"Cheap date" activities dramatically outpace expensive ones:**
- Watching children play sports (61%) vs. Shopping at Brooks Brothers (19%) — 3.2x ratio
- Planning investments (86%) vs. Shopping at Saks Fifth Avenue (26%) — 3.3x ratio
- Praying (47%) vs. Shopping at Brooks Brothers (19%) — 2.5x ratio
- Entertaining close friends (88%) vs. Shopping via Internet (22%) — 4.0x ratio
- Socializing with children/grandchildren (93%) vs. Shopping at Brooks Brothers (19%) — 4.9x ratio
- Taking photographs (67%) vs. Off-roading via 4x4 (5%) — 13.4x ratio

- **Nearly half (47%) of millionaires engaged in prayer** — major force in their lives
- Religious faith underlies economic and spiritual success (see Chapter 4)
- "Cheap date" activities enhance productivity, not just save money

### The Opportunity Cost of DIY

- Typical millionaire earns **>$320/hour** from main vocation
- Installing a shelf: 1 hour to saw/sand/finish + shopping time + installation = 3-4 hours total
- **A $10 shelf actually costs $1,050-$1,400 in lost opportunity**
- Most millionaires avoid do-it-yourself tasks for economic reasons
- **Strong negative correlation between time spent playing golf and do-it-yourself activities**
- Golf justifies expenses and opportunity costs — it's about cultivating customers and keeping current ones happy

> "It's not golf. The real game on the fairway is cultivating new customers and keeping current ones happy."

### A Twelve-Month Diary

**Top Activities (Annual Basis):**
1. Consulting with tax expert — 85%
2. Going to museums — 81%
3. Community/civic activities — 68%
4. Gardening — 67%
5. Raising funds for charity — 64%

**Bottom of the List (Under 25%):**
- Skiing in Rockies (22%), Alps (4%)
- Sailing on yacht (20%)
- Gambling at casinos (25%)
- Vacationing in Palm Springs (17%)
- Attending Grand Slam tennis (11%)
- Taking ocean cruise around world (3%)

- **All stereotypical "millionaire activities" rank in bottom half on frequency scale**
- Most activities very different from lavish lifestyles of high-income nonmillionaires
- Pseudo-affluent lifestyle among nonmillionaires explains why most high-living people never become wealthy

### Tax Consulting: The #1 Activity

- **85% consulted with tax expert in past year**
- Typical millionaire paid >$300,000 in taxes last year
- Nearly 1 in 5 paid >$1 million in taxes
- **Those with annual income $1M+ = <0.1% of households but account for 14.7% of all income tax collected**
- Even 5-10% tax reduction = paying for child's college tuition
- **Only 30% prepare own taxes; 1/3 of those are CPAs or tax attorneys**
- **Strong negative correlation between do-it-yourself activities and wealth**

**Do-it-yourself activities negatively correlated with wealth (ranked by significance):**
1. Mowing your own lawn
2. Do-it-yourself plumbing
3. Preparing your own taxes
4. Painting your home's exterior

- Lower wealth levels = higher tendency for DIY activities
- **Do-it-yourself activities are substitutes to building wealth**
- Mrs. Stanley's reaction: "Millionaires... not doing things around the home! What do they do with their spare time?"
- Dr. Stanley: "They are involved in activities that enhance their wealth."

### The Most Significant Substitute

**Playing the lottery has the strongest inverse relationship with net worth:**
- Higher net worth = less likely to ever play lottery (33% played in past year)
- **The higher a person's net worth, the less likely he is to ever play the lottery**

### Outside the Office: Raising Funds for Charity

- **64% engaged in fund-raising for charity** (rank #5)
- Very strong positive correlation between fund-raising and net worth
- **Not dominated by seniors or inherited wealth** — most millionaires were raising funds before becoming financially independent
- Noble intent drives participation, not just wealth
- Fund-raising clusters economically productive people who appreciate each other
- People seen at their best in noble causes — enhances reputation and integrity

> "If you wish to become affluent, associate with economically productive people."

### Art, Entertainment, and Travel

- **57% took overseas vacations** (decamillionaires even more likely)
- Not all vacations are pure pleasure — many blend business, investing, and pleasure
- Tax advantages exist for blending business with pleasure (consult CPA/tax attorney first)
- Gray areas about blending business, pleasure, and art/antique investments
- Productive people have more opportunities to accomplish this blending
- Many have vacations subsidized through business/professional activities

**Example: Dr. Edwards (physician, $1M annual income)**
- Constantly keeps up with medical innovations
- Writes/publishes research articles
- Invited to present at regional, national, international medical conventions
- Receives modest stipend ($1,000) + lodging paid + frequent-flier miles accumulated
- Can fly whole family anywhere free with accumulated miles
- **Kills two birds with one stone:** presentation = business cost, plus vacation for family
- Can purchase/invest in original art and attend antique auctions in Europe

### Table 9-6: Tax Expert vs. "Tonier" Activities

**Millionaires are 3-85 times more likely to consult tax experts than do luxury activities:**
- Consulting with tax expert (85%) vs. Vacationing in Paris (20%) = **4.3x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Skiing in Rockies (22%) = **3.9x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Skiing in Alps (4%) = **21.3x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Grand Slam tennis (11%) = **7.7x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Sailing on yacht (20%) = **4.3x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Palm Springs (17%) = **5.0x ratio**
- Tax expert (85%) vs. Ocean cruise (3%) = **28.3x ratio**

**Fund-raising for charity also dramatically outpaces luxury travel:**
- Raising funds (64%) vs. Paris (20%) = **3.2x ratio**
- Raising funds (64%) vs. Skiing in Alps (4%) = **16.0x ratio**
- Raising funds (64%) vs. Grand Slam tennis (11%) = **5.8x ratio**
- Raising funds (64%) vs. Sailing on yacht (20%) = **3.2x ratio**
- Raising funds (64%) vs. Ocean cruise (3%) = **21.3x ratio**

- Extravagant consumption is out, fund-raising is in among millionaires
- Ellen (new market researcher focused on fund-raising) correct in her assertion
- **Fund-raising outpaces all "tonier" luxury activities by wide margins**

## Chapter 9: A Wake-up Call

### The Early Bird Myth

- **No statistically significant correlation between wake-up time and wealth**
- Typical millionaire wakes at **6:40 AM** (median ~6:25 AM)
- Only 1 in 5 rises before 5:40 AM
- Early rising alone doesn't make millionaires — would be too easy

**Author's caddy experience:**
- As youngest caddy (12 years old), always assigned to "Bob and Andy Ancient" (late 80s/90s)
- Had to carry their bags AND folding seats
- Took 6-8 hours for 18 holes including 90-minute lunch
- Never broke $10 in tips despite "mulligans"
- But they were **multimillionaires, household names in American industry**
- Senior caddies complained about "playing favorites" by caddy master

**The "first in, first out" system:**
- Club adopted objective assignment: caddy arriving first gets first twosome/foursome
- Stanley arrived 7:00 AM first Saturday — already filled with caddies
- Next Saturday: woke at 4:00 AM, biked to club, arrived before 5:30 AM
- Still 5-6 fellows ahead — early arrivals sleeping on men's room floor since 11:00 PM night before
- **Couldn't win the "earliest arrival" contest**

### Productivity Over Punctuality

- Self-made millionaires selected vocations rewarding productivity during working hours
- **Not what time people start workday that makes them successful — it's how productive they are during working hours**
- Best teachers/professors not usually paid more than less productive (except most competitive colleges)
- "First in" mentality not tolerated by ambitious, productive people
- **Seniority should only be relevant when objective performance measures are given most weight**
- Without performance incentives, productive people move on or become less productive

### The Innovation Advantage

- Getting up early isn't difficult and doesn't require great intelligence
- **Being first is important for innovation** — beat those who prioritize arriving early over developing creative products
- Let "me too" product makers wake before dawn
- Working 12-hour days may be requirement to join cutthroat industry
- **Very few millionaires are civil servants** — completely different orientation
- Want compensation based on performance, no other way
- Would never motivate themselves in "first to arrive" environment

### Dr. Bill Darden's Productivity Schedule

**Dr. Bill Darden (author's graduate school mentor, leading lifestyle researcher):**
- Arrived mid-to-late morning hours
- Office always open, very kind to graduate students
- Actually had **two workday mornings:**
  1. **1:00 AM - 3:00 AM:** writing programs, "crunching numbers," then bed
  2. **9:00 AM arrival:** between 10:00-11:00 AM at office
- No graduate assistant to do computational work
- Most early mornings: working, writing programs, crunching numbers
- Fellow students thought he started 10:00-11:00 AM — **at least half wrong**

**Author discovered his schedule:**
- Entered computer center 2:00 AM to run large programs on late-night shift
- Found Dr. Darden running his programs
- Stanley's books/papers completed faster with 3-4 hour daily writing sessions (not 8-10 hours)
- **Quality of writing matters, not ten-hour days**
- If writer's brain shuts down after 3-4 hours, six-hour days = pure junkola

**Key insight:**
- Hard-charging entrepreneurs awakening at 3:00 AM = myth
- **No statistically significant difference among millionaires in various occupational groups re: wake-up time**
- Senior corporate executives wake slightly earlier on average (not significant difference)
- Computer center always too crowded/distracting during normal office hours
- Darden's best work showed up before dawn when others asleep
- **When are you most productive?** If not 8:00-5:00, consider changing schedule (easier when self-employed)

## Chapter 10: A Final Note About the Millionaire Mind

### Think Differently from the Crowd

- Author never interested in studying "beautiful people"
- Beautiful people supposedly destined to succeed: extremely high IQs, top grades, top schools, great looks, tall with blue eyes, Division I athletes, trace ancestry to Battle of Hastings 1066, earn millions yearly, play par golf, on every noble cause board, no cavities/physical ailments, five supermodel spouses, etc.

**Why no interest in "beautiful people"?**
- **Never met one millionaire with all these qualities**
- Yet nonmillionaires think beautiful people = bulk of millionaire population
- Author most interested in people like **Paule Rossmann** (fighter pilot ace with injured arm from Chapter 1)
- Compensated for deficiency, adjusted to problem
- **Lack of one key attribute = catalyst for change in strategy**
- Became ace by tapping creative sense


<!-- pp. 381-394 -->

### The Rossmann Lesson: Imperfection as Advantage

- **Paule Rossmann** defeated physically superior fighter pilots by selecting target, time, place, altitude, angle of attack strategically
- Avoided direct confrontations with "beautiful people" who had physical advantages
- Proactive approach: shot down opponents before they realized he had "only one good arm"
- Mentored **Erich Hartmann**, the Ace of Aces, holder of world record for air victories

### The Value of Imperfection in Economic Success

- Stanley prefers mentors who overcame imperfections, not "beautiful people"
- **Contrarian claim**: Many millionaires say if they were beautiful, they would never have become productive
- Being beautiful removes the need to be careful in selecting ideal vocation
- Imperfection forces strategic thinking about competitive advantage

> "I want someone who is not a beautiful person. I want to learn about how to become economically productive from those who had one or more imperfections. They are the ones who figured out how to win."

## Profile: Donald and Winifred Sonner, Southern Bloomer Manufacturing Company

### Early Life and First Fortune

- **Donald Sonner**, 64, head of Southern Bloomer Manufacturing in Bristol, Tennessee
- Never had a traditional job working for others
- Became millionaire first time at age 24
- Has been "up and down the ladder many times" since
- Grew up on farm working "awful hard"

> "In those days we had to get our mail from a post office that was in a country store, and I would go to the store for the mail."

- Observed traveling peddlers with "more money than God" selling gloves, pipes, socks
- At 15, bought second-hand socks in North Carolina, couldn't sell them to stores
- Sold socks at sawmill camps instead, made "pretty good profit"

> "I knew more what I was looking for."

### Building a Business on Seconds and Scrap

- Built fortune by finding unusual markets for less-than-top-quality goods
- **Business model**: "I'm in the junk business. I'm the guy that buys the seconds, the odd-lot cloth, out of textile mills. I'm their dumpster man."
- Capital advantage: has money to buy cloth whether moving it or not, like used-auto-parts business
- Last resort: turn unsold goods into rags and sell to industries

### The Gun Patch Innovation

- Nearly cornered market for gun-cleaning patches made from scrap cloth
- Made from scraps from cutting-room and sewing-room floors (imperfect cloth)
- People initially laughed: "He can't last long"

> "But this was money from heaven: I had an endless supply. And it has grown into a substantial business for us."

### Prison Garment Market Discovery

- Began making underpants for prisoners after losing all his fortune
- Lost fortune meant no need for uniform, first-quality goods—could start smaller

> "There was a mental institution up the road and I said, 'They got women there.' They needed an item that would go through their big heavy steam laundry. By buying this odd-lot cloth, I could give them a lot for their money. And with this little operation, I could put a lot of sewing into it."

### Other Markets

- **Sawmills**: second-quality socks
- **Military**: gun patches
- **Prisons and mental institutions**: second-quality garments made from odd-lot cloth

> "When you have something to sell, you've got to learn where there's a market."

### Adapting to Market Changes

- Big chains erased old market of thousands of smaller stores
- Smaller businesses must be more creative, develop ideas requiring less capital

### Partnership with Winifred

- **Winifred Sonner** runs business with him as great partner
- She spearheads marketing, he handles manufacturing

> "She's a gorgeous woman, but she's gorgeous in the inside too... and willing to fight to win."

- His first wife was "a little country girl from the mountains"
- Made money selling women's apparel early on
- Money became important to first wife to point where "she was rotten with it"

> "Money affects some people differently."

> "Winifred and I are comfortable with each other regardless of where we are. We make a tremendous team. I don't know who's the boss, but there's a kind of a magic between us."

### Business Philosophy

> "You have to like what you're doing—like a rabbit dog. You chase this rabbit and forget about everything else but the rabbit. You have to live it, but you get enjoyment out of some success in it."

- Only one year of high school education
- Educational background less important than "will to win"

> "I do not have a great education: just a year of high school. You develop a feel for ideas that don't take much money. I don't think educational background in most cases is as important as the will to win."

### Frugal Lifestyle

- Watches costs carefully—hard-learned lesson he recommends for young entrepreneurs
- Doesn't try to impress others
- Could drive any car but drives '88 model minivan in good shape (bought used in '90 for $5,000)
- Drives '82 Volvo (paid $3,000)
- Clean, nice cars—not about impressing

> "A self-made person is not a person generally who's trying to impress someone."

### Advice Against Borrowing

> "[Borrowing] a lot of money for a new business is the worst thing in the world. If you don't have any money, you learn how to do things without. If you have money, you make mistakes. The more money, the bigger the mistakes."

- Paying interest 24 hours/day, 7 days/week
- Without banks pressuring, forces discipline

> "If you don't have any banks breathing down your throat maybe you don't do as much—but it doesn't take so much to feed them."

### The Inventory Trap

> "Inventory is the death of a lot of small businesses. I always thought the produce business was good, because you either sell it or you smell it, so you learn to make it move."

- Must sacrifice, learn to do with less to grow business
- Second and third-generation kids can't keep parents' business growing because they didn't experience the sacrifices

> "You learn to do with less and, in turn, you grow the business. That's the reason second-and third-generation kids can't keep their parents' business growing. Their parents watched out for the pitfalls, and the kids don't have that experience."

### Career Choice Advice

> "You've got to do one of two things. Either have a master's degree in a good field or work like hell and use your mind to start something small."

## The Eight Parts: Economic Success Equation

Stanley summarizes the Sonner case as "true-to-life pro forma of economic success" demonstrating hard work, focus, courage, unconventional product offerings, and choice of spouse.

**The eight elements of economic success:**

1. **Hard work, integrity, and focus** — key success factors the economy continues to reward
2. **Never let lackluster academic record block economic productivity** — educational credentials don't determine success
3. **Have courage to take financial risk and learn to overcome defeat** — resilience matters
4. **Select unique and profitable vocation you love** — passion and differentiation both required
5. **Be careful selecting spouse** — economically productive people marry compatible partners
6. **Operate economically productive household** — many millionaires prefer to repair/refinish rather than buy new
7. **Follow millionaire lead when selecting home** — study, search, negotiate aggressively
8. **Adopt balanced lifestyle** — millionaires are "cheap dates," doesn't take much money to enjoy family and friends

## Appendix 1: In Search of the Balance Sheet Affluent

### Targeting by Neighborhood

- Estimated incidence of millionaire households for each of 226,399 Census Block Groups/neighborhoods
- Millionaire households defined by **net worth**, not income
- Used proprietary methodology developed by **Jon Robbin**
- Methodology: adjusts unearned income for underreporting, capitalizes with rational rate of real return, estimates net worth via nonlinear fit to **Lorenz curve**
- Data sources: Survey of Consumer Finance (Federal Reserve), IRS Statistics of Income series
- Produced rank ordering of all 226,399 neighborhoods by descending millionaire incidence
- Selected highest incidence areas for identifying sample

### Sample Strategy

- Selected randomly from neighborhoods with over 30% millionaire incidence
- Stratified sample for increasingly higher proportion of millionaires at higher incidence levels
- 2,487 neighborhoods selected, estimated to contain highest concentrations of millionaire households
- Commercial list organizations supplied head-of-household names/addresses for ~95% of Census-tabulated homes
- Purged addresses with 3+ lines or multiple names at same phone number (likely commercial)
- Over 5,000 households selected at random from enumerated households

### National Survey Execution

- **Survey period**: May 20, 1998 to August 24, 1998
- 5,063 households received nine-page questionnaire, form letter, one dollar bill incentive, business reply envelope
- **Response rate**: 19.8% (1,001 surveys completed)
- **Millionaire households**: 733 out of 1,001 respondents = 73.2% had net worth $1 million or more

### A Pretest Sample

- Supplemented with alternative **ad hoc survey**
- Useful because sophisticated geocoding typically ignores millionaires in areas with lower concentrations
- Used as pretest for questionnaire design and methodology
- All 638 millionaire respondents had income/balance sheet credentials qualifying them for jumbo mortgages

